<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: U.N. Faces Challenges of Peace, Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 29 (Xinhua) -- As bells ring worldwide on
New Year's Eve to greet the arrival of the last year in this decade,
also the last one in the outgoing century, guns are still rattling in
Afghanistan, the Balkans, the Great Lake region and West Africa.
</P>
<P>
When consumers in some countries go shopping for Christmas
season and New Year celebrations, many people in other parts of
the world are groaning under the negative impact of the global
economic and financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
This is the reality in today's world, signalling the 185-nation
United Nations is facing grave challenges of peace and security, and
economic and social crisis in the new year.
</P>
<P>
"In the coming year, we face a double challenge. There is perennial
challenge of international peace and security. And there is the
challenge of economic and social crisis, which really means the
challenge of globalization and global governance," U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan has said.
</P>
<P>
None of the crisis in Afghanistan, Africa, the Balkans have been
resolved. In Kosovo, all-out war was avoided for the time being, but
the U.K.-U.S. missile and air strikes on Iraq had dashed popular hope
to see a peaceful exit of the Year 1998.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council, in charge of world peace and
security under the U.N. Charter, is still fighting over how to
formally respond to the just-concluded London-Washington military
action against Iraq, which, launched in the absence of the Council's
authorization, has been seen as a violation of the Charter and norms
of international law.
</P>
<P>
Over the outgoing year, the crises have taken up enormous
amount of the world body's time. It might be tempting to leave the
economic and social issues to others. But the United Nations
cannot afford to do that.
</P>
<P>
In February this year, Annan, with his successful diplomacy,
defused the Iraqi crisis, thus demonstrating that the United Nations
can play a positive role in safeguarding world peace and security.
</P>
<P>
Although the cold war was over about a decade ago, the cold war
mentality dies hard. A world run by big powers acting outside the
framework of international relations has subjected itself to a
clear threat of power politics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
