<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Education System Not Meet Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Presidential
Commission of Inquiry into Education and Training said Tuesday
the country's education system is too academic and
examination-oriented, making it difficult for high school
graduates to be absorbed by the formal job market.
</P>
<P>
"Teachers concentrate on whether students have passed the
examinations when in fact the students do not have any skills
required by industries, which makes it difficult for them to find
jobs," said Caiphas Nziramasanga, chairman of the commission,
when he presented the interim report to President Robert Mugabe
Tuesday, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Students should be given a chance to develop non-academic
skills which they could excel in, he said, adding that the
current curriculum should be changed to make it relevant to the
needs of the country.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe set up the 12-member commission on January 2 this year
to revamp the country's education system to meet the demands of
industry.
</P>
<P>
Receiving the 69-page report, the president said it would be
thoroughly studied and discussed by the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
He said the inputs from several sectors in compiling the
report was a step in the right direction which would benefit the
whole nation.
</P>
<P>
"I congratulate the commission for the approach it has taken
to produce such a noble contribution which now stands
accomplished and set to benefit our whole nation," said Mugabe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
