<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Civil Servants Demand 20 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Harare, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's civil servants
still demand a 20 percent cost of living adjustment in addition
to the 25 percent salary increase the government awarded them
Monday, the Public Service Association (PSA) said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
PSA acting executive secretary Charles Chiviru said in a
statement that the PSA considered the 25 percent offer as a
"pre-payment of whatever outcome of the results of the
arbitration between staff associations and government
representatives."
</P>
<P>
He said the civil servants were still demanding the 20 percent
increase that had been given to private sector workers.
</P>
<P>
The increase followed demands by the Zimbabwe Congress Trade
of Unions, which said the adjustment was necessary to cushion
workers against the rising cost of most basic goods.
</P>
<P>
"Since last Wednesday, pressure is mounting on us from our
members who are demanding the 20 percent awarded to the private
sector," Chiviru said.
</P>
<P>
He warned that PSA members might be forced to take action
before the end of January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
