<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Wants to Slash German Budget Payments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 29 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder wants to slash German budget payments to the European
Union by adding black-market revenue to raise GDP figures for
countries like Italy, the news magazine Stern said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder's economics advisor, Klaus Gretschmann, has called
for gross domestic product (GDP) to be calculated with the
inclusion of suspected black-market income, said Stern. This,
Gretschmann argues, would allow Germany to cut its E.U.
contribution.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation European Union (E.U.) uses GDP to calculate much
of the annual budget contribution to Brussels by member states.
States with higher GDP pay more.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder has demanded Germany's yearly net E.U. contribution
of 22 billion marks (13.1 billion dollars) be slashed. Decision on
the E.U. budget for the period 2000 to 2006 must be reached next
year given the bloc's current financial arrangements expire at the
end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Germany takes over the E.U. presidency for the first half of
1999 and Schroeder has vowed to resolve the budget question and
farm subsidy reform by March.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1998, NO.2 Worst Year for Natural Disasters Since WWII </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 29 (Xinhua) -- 1998 was one of the worst years
on record for natural disasters, the German Munich
Rueckversicherung (reinsurance) group said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
More than 50,000 people died as a result of earthquakes,
flooding and storms with the combined damage amounting to more
than 90 billion U.S. dollars, the second highest amount in any one
year since the end of the Second World War, the group said.
</P>
<P>
Munich Rueckversicherung, the world's largest reinsurance
group, said that in 1998 it paid out in more than 700 major cases
of damage, about 100 more than in other recent years.
</P>
<P>
The most common was storm and flood damage, which together
accounted for 85 percent of economic damage caused by natural
disasters.
</P>
<P>
The company pointed out however that the insurance industry
made good only about 15 percent of the damage because in most
countries where natural catastrophes occurred, insurance coverage
was not widespread.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwandan and Ugandan Presidents Meet in Southwest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Rwandan president Pasteur
Bizimungu and his Ugandan counterpart, Yoweri Museveni, are in a
meeting since Tuesday morning, the office of the president in
Kigali Tuesday told the Rwanda News Agency (RNA).
</P>
<P>
The meeting opened in Kable Town, in southwestern Uganda, on
the border between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"The meeting between the two heads of states is in the context
of regular consultations on bilateral and regional issues which
are likely to include the Congolese crisis," said presidential
spokesman Joseph Bideri.
</P>
<P>
"It has nothing to do with The monitor's allegations that
Rwanda and Uganda are in disagreement about the on-going conflict
in the Congo," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
According to Bideri, the meeting between Museveni and
Bizimungu was scheduled on Saturday, but was postponed because
the Rwandan president had to attend to other urgent state
affairs.
</P>
<P>
Well-informed sources in capital Kigali have indicated that
both presidents would discuss the proposed peace deal to end
fighting in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) which was
expected to be signed during the aborted Lusaka summit.
</P>
<P>
The Sunday Monitor newspaper had alleged that Rwandan troops
in the DRC are not getting along with their Ugandan counterparts.
The paper had reported a battle between the Rwandan Patriotic
Army (RPA) and the Ugandan People's Defense Force (UPDF) in Isiro
and Buta, two towns in northeastern Congo.
</P>
<P>
The paper had indicated that 30 Rwandan soldiers, and eight
Ugandans had perished in the clashes which took place earlier
this month. Rwandan army spokesman Major Emmanuel Ndahiro told
RNA that the reported clashes were a fabrication, saying that
Rwanda and Uganda were not in a disagreement over the support to
the rebels fighting President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
It was alleged that while Rwanda supports the main rebel
group, the Congolese Rally for Democracy (RCD) chaired by
professor Ernest Wamba Dia Wamba, Uganda was rather favorable to
the newly-born Congolese Liberation Movement (MLC) led by Jean
Pierre Bemba.
</P>
<P>
Major Ndahiro disclosed that the incident which took place in
eastern Congo actually involved UPDF soldiers and the RCD rebels,
after the UPDF field officers attempted to pass the RCD recruits
under Bemba's command. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghana to Implement Value Added Tax System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Ghana will join scores of
nations in the world to adopt the value added tax (VAT) system
Wednesday as it tries to broaden the tax base, the Ghana News
Agency (GNA) reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday, December 30, will mark the re-introduction of VAT
which survived for only three-and-a-half months when it was first
introduced in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The new tax which has been pegged by the parliament at 10
percent will replace the 15 percent sales and service taxes which
have been in operation since early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
Apart from enhancing the country's revenue base, the
implementation of VAT will bring Ghana in line with an Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS) protocol that makes it
mandatory for its members to adopt the tax by the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Most countries in the 16-member sub-regional body, especially
in the Francophone zone, have already switched to VAT.
</P>
<P>
However, different internal economic dynamics of member
countries could be the reason why others should be late in
implementing the tax which experts say is more efficient and
broad-based.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, for instance, Ghana's volatile economic factors such
as the fast depreciation of its currency, the Cedi, high
inflation and high prices of goods and services did not favor the
introduction of the tax.
</P>
<P>
"While all these factors have been brought under control and
we are experiencing a stable economic climate, the elaborate
public education will also work to favor the implementation of
the tax this time round," an official of the VAT Secretariat told
the GNA.
</P>
<P>
The optimism of the Secretariat is buoyed by the high number
of traders who have registered to collect VAT.
</P>
<P>
By Monday, 7,376 traders had registered with the Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
"Even though this is lower than the over 10,000 traders
registered in 1995, it is far higher than what we expected to
register," the official said.
</P>
<P>
Initially, the VAT Secretariat anticipated that 6,000 traders
would register while the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
projected that only 2,000 would register.
</P>
<P>
The good turn-out could possibly be attributed to the intense
public education and expanded business environment since 1995.
</P>
<P>
The threshold which is now pegged at 200 million Cedis (about
85,653 Dollars) compared with 25 million Cedis in 1995 may also
explain the shortfall of registered traders from the 1995 number.
</P>
<P>
"The threshold has cut off quite a number of traders who had
problems in computing VAT which led to increase in prices in
1995," the VAT official said.
</P>
<P>
Perhaps, this has also helped the Secretariat's public
educational team to focus on group on a one-on-one basis to teach
them how to compute the tax.
</P>
<P>
But, public reaction on the re-introduction of VAT, passed by
parliament in February under Act 546, has been quiet and people
appeared to have adopted a wait-and-see attitude.
</P>
<P>
"I think there has been enough public education on VAT this
time and it will only be well for us to give it a try," said
Kwame Agyenim Boateng, a trader in Accra who has registered to
collect VAT.
</P>
<P>
A smooth implementation of VAT will be a relief to the
government which has argued that the sales and service taxes are
not wide enough.
</P>
<P>
Whatever the internal hiccups may be, the implementation will
satisfy the requirement of ECOWAS and Ghana will be part of the
larger body of nations which have adopted it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
