<HEADLINE> U.N. Plane Wreck Appears "Intact": S. African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The wreck of a United
Nations chartered aircraft that crashed in eastern Angola
Saturday had been seen and appeared to be reasonably intact, the
South African embassy in Luanda said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
U.N. officials flew over the scene of the crash late Monday
and an SOS in Morse code had been received from the plane, South
African Press Association quoted a spokesman of the embassy as
saying.
</P>
<P>
But he would not speculate on whether anyone survived.
</P>
<P>
The Hercules C130 transport plane, carrying four crew and 10
passengers, apparently went down in flames east of Vila Nova,
about 45 kilometers from Huambo, in central Angola, on Saturday.
Seven of the passengers were members of the U.N. observer mission
in Angola, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Two of the remaining three passengers were employed by a
Danish non-governmental organization, and the other one an
employee of a security company. The pilot was South African.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the U.N. observer mission in Angola had
requested the Angolan government and the rebel National Union for
the Total Independence of Angola to allow them safe entry into
the area to search and rescue the victims.
</P>
<P>
"They are still awaiting a response," he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the area, where heavy fighting was reported
recently, was reportedly quiet on Tuesday. "But anything can
change in a minute," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
