<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of the
Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) will hold a brief meeting Tuesday
in Saudi capital Riyadh to coordinate stance ahead of the coming
Arab foreign ministerial meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Arab foreign ministerial meeting, designed to discuss a
proposed Arab summit and originally scheduled for Tuesday in
Cairo, was postponed to January 24 due to the rifts among Gulf
states.
</P>
<P>
Arab League Secretary General Ahmed Esmat Abdel-Meguid said in
Cairo Monday that the meeting was put off at the request of the
six-member GCC.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti First Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Sabah
Al-Ahmad Al-Jaber Al-Sabah arrived in Riyadh Tuesday to attend the
brief meeting, the Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
But it did not say if the other four foreign ministers of the
GCC, which groups Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and
the United Arab Emirates, had arrived.
</P>
<P>
On December 20, Yemen proposed to hold an emergency Arab summit
to discuss the latest developments in the Arab world, especially
those after the U.S.-British air strikes on Iraq, and seek ways of
restoring Arab solidarity.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain bombed Iraqi targets on four successive
nights December 16-19, with a declared aim of punishing Baghdad
for its failure to fully cooperate in U.N. weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
The inspections began in 1991 after the Gulf War, which was set
off by Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990, to ensure Iraq's
elimination of all its weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The last GCC summit held in the United Arab Emirates earlier
December had stressed the need to enhance Arab relations and exert
more efforts to restore Arab solidarity on principles and rules of
joint Arab action. 
</P>
