<HEADLINE> Romanian Government Adopts 1999 Draft Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The Romanian government
Tuesday adopted the 1999 draft state budget during its last
meeting this year.
</P>
<P>
Under the draft budget, projected revenues for 1999 are likely
to reach 84,756 billion lei (7.8 billion U.S. dollars), and
outlays 90,976 billion lei (8.4 billion U.S. dollars), the deficit
is expected to drop from 3.6 percent of this year to 2 percent of
the Gross Domestic Product.
</P>
<P>
State budget allotments will avail of 16,922 billion lei (1.6
billion U.S. dollars) less than they had in 1998, several
ministries being allotted less than the already shoestring 1998
funds, Finance Minister Decebal Traian Remes told the press after
the draft was passed by the government.
</P>
<P>
He announced that the main profit sources for the next year's
budget would be the wage tax, the value added tax, customs duties,
excise taxes.
</P>
<P>
The minister said he was aware nobody would be happy with the
budget, adding he was forced to resort to restrictions due to the
country's currently poor economic level and an overdue foreign
debt worth 2 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"In Romania a budget revival is expected by mid-1999, further
commitments from banks and further access to new financing. I
don't have the impression that Romania is in a deadlock, but it is
true that we must bring our own contribution to improve the
current state of facts," Remes said.
</P>
<P>
He voiced hope the Permanent Offices of the Parliament's Two
Houses would hold an extraordinary sitting around January 25,
which would make it possible for the draft budget to pass early in
February.  
</P>
</TEXT>
