by some African leaders such as President Nelson Mandela of South
Africa and President Frederick Chiluba of Zambia to find a
peaceful solution to the five-month-old conflict in the third
largest African country.
</P>
<P>
They said they are ready to continue cooperation in all these
aspects, dismissing some media rumors that have alleged that
there were conflicts or problems between Ugandan and Rwandan
soldiers deployed in DRC.
</P>
<P>
On the situation in Angola, the two leaders regretted the
resumption of fighting in that country and called upon the
international community to ensure that the fighting is brought to
an end in accordance with U.N. Security Council resolutions and
the 1994 Lusaka Protocol.
</P>
<P>
Both leaders emphatically denied any involvement by their two
countries in the war in Angola.
</P>
<P>
Museveni returned home Monday from his three-day visit to
Tripoli where he held talks with Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi on
the situation in the Great Lakes region. 
