<HEADLINE> U.S. Existing Home Sales Rise 2.7 Percent in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Washington, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. national
Association of Realtors said Tuesday that sales of existing homes
jumped 2.7 percent in November to a seasonally adjusted rate of
4.9 million-homes per year, as compared with a rate of 4.79
million in October.
</P>
<P>
With last month's strong showing, the Association ratcheted up
its projection for this year to 4.78 million sales, up 13.5
percent from the record 4.22 million set in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The increase has been stimulated by plentiful jobs, big
accumulated stock market gains and low mortgage rates, the
Association said. New homes have also been selling at a record
pace this year. Economists expected strong home sales would
continue into 1999.
</P>
<P>
According to today's survey of the Conference Board, a
business-financed private research group based in New York,
consumers were slightly more positive in December about the
U.S.current state of the economy than they were in November.
