<HEADLINE> 74 Burundi Refugees Enter Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations High
Commission for Refugees (UNHCR) and the Ministry of Home Affairs
office in western Kigoma Region are screening 74 Burundi refugees
who recently entered Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The screening of the refugees who fled from Kalemie and Moba
in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) is being carried out
very carefully as some are suspected to be combatants, a refugee
situation report issued by UNHCR Tanzania branch said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report, however, did not mention the date when the
refugees entered Tanzania but said they were transported to
Kigoma from Kirando in Rukwa Region in southwest Tanzania Monday
last week together with 12 other refugees from DRC.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the report said 428 refugees from DRC and Burundi
entered the country through Kigoma between December 18 and
Monday, bringing the number of refugees from the two countries
currently in Kigoma camps to 22,060, with 17,833 from DRC and
4,227 from Burundi.
</P>
<P>
The report said the new arrivals from DRC included two severe
malnourishing children, two pregnant women and one person
suffering a chronic disease suspected to be tuberculosis, all of
whom have been admitted to a transit center.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the DRC refugees came from Fizi,
Uvira, and Kalemie. Those from Fizi and Uvira said they fled from
harassment, forced recruitment and looting by both the rebels and
government soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Those from Kalemie said there were occasional fightings in
their area between the rebels and the Mayimayi soldiers
supporting the Congolese government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
