<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Locates 22,700 Land-mines in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique has located 22,737
anti-personnel land-mines this year, over three times the figure
of 6,212 in 1997, a senior official said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Osorio Mateus, Director of National Land-mine Clearance
Bureau, said that they have also located 30 anti-tank mines, and
70,000 other bombs during the period.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference on the achievement of 1998's land-mine
clearance work, Mateus said the land mines and bombs were found
along 90-km railways lines, 24-km high-voltage power lines, and a
length of 612-km roads.
</P>
<P>
The land-mine clearance authorities also removed land mines on
1,051 hectares of land this year, compared with the 467 hectares
of land in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The government spent about 18.5 million U.S. Dollars on
land-mine clearance in 1998, two million Dollars more than the
figure of last year, he said.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that after land-mine knowledge education in the
country, much fewer land mine disasters were reported this year
than before.
</P>
<P>
So far Mozambique has cleared 53,136 anti-personnel land
mines, 331 anti-tank mines and tens of thousands of bombs ever
since 1993 when it started its land mine clearance plan.
</P>
<P>
About one to two million land mines had been planted in the
country in its 16-year-long civil war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
