<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus President Decides not to Deploy S-300 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus President Glafcos
Clerides announced Wednesday night that he has decided not to
deploy the Russian-made S-300 anti-aircraft missiles in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
He said in a two-page written statement after a three-hour
session of the National Council that he would negotiate with the
Russian government the possible deployment of the missiles in
Greece's Crete island.
</P>
<P>
Clerides's decision followed his talks with Greek Prime
Minister Costas Simitis in the Greek capital of Athens earlier in
the day on the future of the Russian S-300 missiles ordered by
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
After the talks, Clerides returned to Cyprus for the meeting of
the National Council, the top advisory body to the president on
the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus ordered the surface-to-air missiles in January 1997 in a
bid to cement its air defense capability.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, the close ally of independence-seeking Turkish Cypriots
in Cyprus, has threatened to launch a preemptive strike on the
missiles if they are deployed in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The U.N., the U.S. and Britain have also expressed opposition
to the deployment of the missiles, which they said will increase
tensions on the Mediterranean island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
