<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Retreats From Key S. Leonean Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 29 (Xinhua) -- ECOMOG, the West African
peace-keeping force in Sierra Leone has retreated from the
strategic town of Makeni in the northeast, after almost a week of
fierce fighting with the rebels.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here quoted an ECOMOG statement as saying
Tuesday that the retreat is "tactical", adding that a
pro-government militia group is still putting up defense there.
</P>
<P>
The rebels launched their offensive on Makeni, about 100
kilometers from Sierra Leonean capital Freetown last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leonean Foreign Minister Sam Banya said Monday that
virtually the entire population of several thousand people had
fled the town.
</P>
<P>
He also claimed that mercenaries from Liberia, Burkina Faso
and Ukraine are fighting alongside the rebels.
</P>
<P>
The Liberian government has denied the accusation.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG's loss in Makeni came one day after foreign ministers
of the Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) met in
Abidjan Monday to discuss the situation in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The one-day meeting appealed to the rebels to lay down their
arms and seek to solve the crisis through dialog. It also called
for more troops from members countries to defend the elected
government of President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
In the face of intensive rebel attacks in recent weeks,
Nigeria, which already provides the bulk of the 10,000 strong
ECOMOG troops, has sent an additional 1,000 soldiers to Freetown.
Ghana has also sent fresh reinforcements.
</P>
<P>
About 500 soldiers from Mali and Gambia are also expected
within days, while other west African countries have also pledged
troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
