<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-29 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: A Compromise Solution to Cyprus' Missiles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus' President Glafcos
Clerides Tuesday night made a compromise solution to the
controversial missiles issue by announcing not to deploy the
Russian S-300 missiles in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
After a session of the National Council, the top advisory body
to the president on the Cyprus issue, Clerides said that he would
negotiate with Russia the possible deployment of the missiles in
Greece's southern island of Crete.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that the compromise decision would ease
the situation and ward off the threat of Turkish military
intervention.
</P>
<P>
But the decision is likely to spark a government crisis on the
island.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist EDEK party, which holds the ministries of defense
and education, and some junior government partners have said that
they will quit the government if Clerides goes back on his
pre-election promise to deploy the missiles in Cyprus. Some
leaders of other parties have asked the president to resign.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus announced in January 1997 to purchase and deploy the
S-300 surface-to-air missiles in an effort to cement its air
defense capability, a move that sparked bitter crisis with Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, the close ally of independence-seeking Turkish Cypriots
in northern Cyprus, has repeatedly threatened to launch a
preemptive strike if the missiles were installed on the island.
</P>
<P>
Western countries, including the United States and Britain,
have warned that the deployment of the missiles could further
destabilize the situation on the divided island.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the European Union hinted that the deployment of the
missiles might jeopardize Cyprus' accession to the union.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the Western concerns arose out of fear that
Moscow would regain influence in the region, and that the deal
would enable Russia to acquire information on the movements of the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization over the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Even Greece, Cyprus' close ally, is not in favor of installing
the missiles in Cyprus and proposed Crete as an alternative.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council adopted a resolution on
December 22, calling on U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan to
intensify efforts towards the settlement of the issue and the
demilitarization of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The delivery of the missiles had already been put off on a
number of occasions in the face of mounting international pressure.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated
south and Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkey
landed its troops and took over the northern third of the island
in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liberia Denies Aiding S. Leonean Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The Liberian government Tuesday
denied the charges that it is aiding rebels trying to topple the
government of neighboring Sierra Leone, a report reaching here
said.
</P>
<P>
A government statement said Liberia is considering withdrawing
from the five-member committee of the Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS) on Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The committee was set up by ECOWAS shortly after the May 1997
coup that ousted elected President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah with four
members initially. Liberia was included in the committee at the
20th ECOWAS summit held in Nigerian capital Abuja in August 1997.
</P>
<P>
The government of Sierra Leone has repeatedly accused Liberia
of supporting the rebels, including supply of weapons and direct
involvement of Liberian soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The same charges were raised against Liberia in a communique
issued Monday at the end of an ECOWAS meeting in Abidjan, capital
of Cote d'Ivoire, on the situation in Sierra Leone, where rebels
have intensified their offensive in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Liberian government said in the statement that it "views
with disappointment and indignation" suggestions that it is
backing the rebels bent on ousting President Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
It said it is Liberia that is being destabilized by what it
called the use of Liberian mercenaries by successive regimes in
Sierra Leone, including the Kabbah government, to bolster their
security.
</P>
<P>
"The government of Liberia considers this situation as grave,"
it said, calling on Kabbah to start a dialog with his opponent as
the only guarantee of peace in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
"The Liberian government further calls on the United Nations
to establish a commission of inquiry with immediate effect to
establish the circumstances leading to the involvement of foreign
nationals, including Liberians, in the Sierra Leone civil war,"
it added.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the accusation against Liberia has created
a crisis of confidence compromising its participation in the
regional committee trying to resolve the conflict.
</P>
<P>
"As a result of the situation, Liberia may be prepared to
recluse (exclude) itself from the process until such a time when
the crisis of confidence is resolved," it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
