<HEADLINE> 4th Western Hostage Dies After Freed in Yemen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANAA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- A fourth Westerner taken hostage
by militant Islamic tribesmen died in hospital Tuesday, after
being wounded by kidnappers.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 16 tourists were abducted by the tribesmen, who
killed three of them in a shoot-out with Yemeni security forces in
a rescue operation earlier Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The fourth one, a Briton, died later in hospital as the other
13 were freed, Yemeni Interior Ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The three killed during the exchange of fire were two Britons
and an Australian. Earlier reports said an American woman was
killed, but the U.S. State Department said she was wounded.
</P>
<P>
Two of the kidnappers and a policeman were also killed in the
shoot-out, while another kidnapper and three policemen were
wounded, an official said.
</P>
<P>
The 16 Westerners - 12 Britons, six of whom women, two American
women and two Australian men - were taken hostage on Monday near
the southern Yemeni town of Mawdiyah, 200 kilometers south of the
capital, when 18 men ambushed the convoy of the tourists.
</P>
<P>
The kidnappers, who were identified by Yemeni security
officials as members of the extremist Islamic Jihad, demanded the
release of two of their leaders who were arrested during Yemeni
government's recent crackdown on Islamic extremists.
</P>
<P>
The Yemeni authorities began negotiations with the abductors
earlier Tuesday for the release of the tourists, which apparently
failed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
