<HEADLINE> Jordan Calls on U.S. to End Attacks on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Jordan called on the United
States Tuesday evening to stop its bombardment of Iraqi air
defense positions under the no-fly zone in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian government is following with grave concern the
latest development in northern Iraq, where U.S warplanes clashed
with Iraqi air defenses on Monday, said Information Minister
Nasir Judeh in a statement after a cabinet meeting on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The statement, the first official response from Jordan
following the latest U.S.-Iraqi confrontations, asked the United
States to stop all military actions in northern Iraq to prevent
further escalation of tensions over the Iraqi issue.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, the Jordanian government reiterated its call
on the U.S to pursue a diplomatic solution to the Iraqi crisis.
</P>
<P>
Sanctions on Iraq should be lifted in accordance with
international laws, putting an end to the sufferings of the
Iraqi people, the statement added.
</P>
<P>
Jordan had condemned the U.S.-British air attacks on Iraq on
December 16-19, which was triggered by what the U.S. said Iraq`s
failure to cooperate fully with U.N. arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The kingdom also hosted a special meeting by the 17-member
Arab Parliamentary Union on December 27, which condemned the
U.S.-led air attacks on Baghdad, and called for lifting the
sanctions on Iraq, imposed after Iraq`s invasion of Kuwait in
1990. 
</P>
