<HEADLINE> Simitis: Greece Supports Cyprus' Decision on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis stressed here Tuesday that his country supported the
decision made by Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides regarding the
deployment of Russian-made anti-aircraft missiles.
</P>
<P>
After consultations with Simitis and Cyprus' National Council
of political leaders, Clerides announced in Nicosia later Tuesday
that Cyprus had abandoned its plan to install the S-300 missiles
in the divided island republic and would negotiate their possible
deployment in the southern Greek island of Crete.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Clerides' decision, Simitis said that it was a
decision which the Greek government fully backed.
</P>
<P>
He added that it was part of the joint defense doctrine
planning, which would boost Cyprus' defense and protection.
</P>
<P>
The responsible decision just taken by Clerides must then be
assessed in the context of a new effort to raise the substance of
the issue through new procedures, the premier said, adding that
the joint Greek-Cypriot effort would now focus on fully exploiting
the dynamics created by these developments.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that military cooperation between the two
countries would continue within the context of the joint defense
pact signed between Athens and Nicosia in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Greece guaranteed the right of Greek Cypriots to live in
security and would continue to defend that right by all means
available, he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Simitis pledged that Greece would promote Cyprus'
accession toward the European Union (EU) as it had done up to now,
believing that Nicosia's admission into the union would safeguard
unhindered and peaceful development and prosperity of the whole of
Cyprus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
