<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam-U.S. Relations Seen "Modest Developments" in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The relations between Vietnam
and the United States have seen "modest developments" in 1998,
Vietnam news agency (VNA) reported Wednesday, quoting a senior
Vietnamese diplomat.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with VNA, Vietnamese ambassador to the U.S. Le
Bang said Vietnam considered the signing of the trade agreement
between the two countries as "the most important task in the
immediate future."
</P>
<P>
"The conditions set by the U.S. side in negotiating a trade
agreement are too difficult for Vietnam" to meet due to the large
gap between the development levels of the two sides, the senior
diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
He said it is time for both countries to show their willingness
to reach such an agreement by taking into consideration the other
party's practical conditions.
</P>
<P>
Only by trying to understand each other and taking into account
the other side's practical situation can the two parties overcome
obstacles and speed up the negotiations for a trade agreement,
Bang said.
</P>
<P>
He described the visit to the U.S. by Deputy Prime Minister and
Foreign Minister Nguyen Manh Cam last October as "successful." The
visit was the first official visit by a Vietnamese governmental
delegation since the two countries normalized relations in 1995.
</P>
<P>
"Another positive development" was U.S. President Bill
Clinton's decision to waive the Jackson-Vanik amendment to
Vietnam, ambassador Bang said.
</P>
<P>
He also recalled the achievements in economic-commercial
relations, which included a 20-percent increase in Vietnam's
export value to the U.S., the signing of an agreement on the
Operation of the Overseas Private Investment Corporation (Opic) in
Vietnam, and exchange of visits by business people of both
countries.
</P>
<P>
U.S. investment in Vietnam totaled 1.4 billion U.S. dollars in
70 projects, ranking the seventh among those countries and regions
investing in Vietnam, Bang said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the two countries are trying to boost cooperation
in science, culture, education and humanitarian issues.
</P>
<P>
However, the ambassador stressed that the economic and
commercial ties have not matched both sides' potential, mainly for
want of a trade agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
