<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia to Import 293,000 Tons of Fertilizer in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The National Fertilizer
Industry Agency of Ethiopia announced Wednesday that the nation
will import 293,000 tons of fertilizer before mid-1999.
</P>
<P>
Zekele Desalegn, general manager of the Agency, told the
Ethiopian News Agency that 108,000 tons of urea and 185,000 tons
of dap will be imported up to May 1999.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia spends an average of over 100 million U.S. Dollars
annually for the purchase of fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
Zekele said the national fertilizer supply for "belg" (small
rainy season, February-May) and "meher" (big rainy season,
June-October) in current Ethiopian year (Ethiopian Calendar 1991
is from September 11, 1998 to September 11, 1999) is expected to
reach over 497,000 tons, adding that there are 204,000 tons of
fertilizer in the country.
</P>
<P>
Fertilizer supply amounted to over 485,000 tons last year, of
which 281,000 tons was utilized up to September 1998, Zekele
said.
</P>
<P>
The general manager noted that despite a marked increase over
the years, the country's fertilizer consumption is still one of
the least by international standards.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia's annual fertilizer demand is expected to reach over
600,000 tons after seven years, said Zekele. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
