<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Expert Calls for Promotion of Arabic on Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The use of Arabic on the
Internet must be promoted to change the situation that other
languages and cultures dominate international communications,
according to a leading Arabic software provider.
</P>
<P>
If effective solutions are not found to promote the use of
Arabic on the Internet, the language will lose its international
significance, Hazem Abdelazim, executive director of Egypt's Sakhr
Software, warned in Emirates News on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The number of Arabic pages on the Internet is 322,898 out of a
total of 20 million web pages, said Abdelazim.
</P>
<P>
"Failing to create effective international quality solutions
for any language would mean that this language will become less
and less significant as information systems using other languages
take center stage in everyday life," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The challenge of the Internet reaches new heights with
languages like Arabic, due to its rich and high inflexional
nature, that requires special technologies not provided by Latin
software," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The cultural, socio-economic and political implications of the
Internet is now motivating big companies, institutes and
governments to respond with a competitive Arabic solution," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Abdelazim will highlight solutions for Arabic on the Internet
when he delivers the key-note address at the Internet World
Middle East '99 (IWME '99) conference and exhibition scheduled
here on February 22-24, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Industry experts from six nations, namely, Egypt, Jordan,
Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Britain and the United
States, will address the conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
