<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq, U.S. Exchange Missile Attack in "No-fly" Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 30 (Xinhua) -- U.S. warplanes fired missiles
and bombs at an Iraqi missile site Wednesday morning after two
British tornado jets came under attack of surface-to-air missiles
in the southern no-fly zone in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
This was the second such incident in three days. On Monday, an
Iraqi missile battery came into confrontation with U.S. warplanes
policing the northern no-fly zone, and four Iraqi soldiers were
killed and seven wounded after U.S. responded with laser-guided
missiles.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's conflict took place at about 9:30 a.m. local time
(6300 GMT), when the two British tornados patroling the southern
no-fly zone stretching from the 33rd latitude southward to the
Gulf were tracked on by Iraqi radar.
</P>
<P>
Western military sources said the Iraqis fired six to eight
SA-2 missiles, an improved version of SA-1 used during the Gulf
War, in which Iraqi troops were defeated by U.S.-led allied forces.
</P>
<P>
Two U.S. F-16 fighter planes came to the Britons' aid,
retaliating with HARM missiles and several precision-guided bombs
on the Iraqi site, reportedly near Talil in southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
All the U.S. and British warplanes returned safely to their
base after the attack.
</P>
<P>
There is no report from the Iraqi side on possible casualties
and damages. Maj Joe LcMarca of the U.S. Central Command told CNN
that "We are in a process of damage assessment" and said he
believed "our ammunitions are accurate."
</P>
<P>
The northern and southern no-fly zones in Iraq were imposed by
the U.S. and its allies in 1991 and 1992 respectively, with
claimed aims of protecting Kurds and Shiite Muslims from troops of
President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Vice President Taha Yassin Ramadan has declared that his
government does not recognize the no-fly zones, set up "illegally"
by the U.S. and its allies without U.N. authorization, and
demanded that the U.N. discuss this issue.
</P>
<P>
"We are operating normally" in these zones, said Ramadan,
meaning Iraqi planes will defy the fly ban and challenge the
U.S. in the areas.
</P>
<P>
U.S. and British forces gathering in the Gulf carried out four
consecutive nights of air strikes against Iraq December 16-19 to
punish Baghdad for not cooperating fully in U.N. weapons
inspections.
</P>
<P>
With their hope for an early lifting of crippling U.N.
sanctions dashed by the air raids, the Iraqis seemed to have
changed their tactics by barring the return of U.N. weapons
inspectors and challenging the U.S. in the no-fly zones.
</P>
<P>
This threatens to turn U.S.-Iraq confrontation into a daily
recurrence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
