<HEADLINE> HK to Host Int'l Meeting on Infrastructure Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) Government announced here today that a
Senior Official-Level Meeting (SOM) for the Third Ministers' Forum
on Infrastructure Development in the Asia-Pacific Region will be
held in Hong Kong from January 6 to 8 next year.
</P>
<P>
Deputies, vice-ministers or senior officials of 14 member
countries and regions including Hong Kong SAR will attend the SOM
at the Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Center to discuss and
agree on an agenda for the Ministers' Forum to be held here next
May. Detailed arrangements for the Forum will also be worked out
at the SOM.
</P>
<P>
The biennial Ministers' Forum provides an arena for ministers
from different entities in the Asia-Pacific region to exchange
ideas and experience in infrastructure development. It also
fosters mutual cooperation among members in dealing with potential
problems arising from infrastructure development. The first two
were held in Japan in 1995 and in Chile in 1997 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The issues to be discussed during the three-day meeting include
the use of information technology for infrastructure development,
high density living in an urban environment, improvement of
regional transportation network/more efficient use of resources by
developing international infrastructure, encouragement of mutual
cooperation for nurturing construction industry, harmony of
infrastructure with the environment, promotion of disaster
prevention measures and securing financial resources for
infrastructure development.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from 20 countries and regions will visit the new Hong
Kong International Airport and the Tung Chung New Town on Lantau,
as well as the Tsing Ma, Kap Shui Mun and Ting Kau bridges.
</P>
</TEXT>
