<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
MANAMA -- Bahraini Emir Sheikh Isa Bin Sulman Al-khalifa said
Tuesday that Bahraini state budget for 1999 and 2000 are expected
to be set at 726 million dinars (1.92 billion U.S. dollars) and
732 million (1.94 billion dollars) respectively.
</P>
<P>
The figures reflect a drop of 0.6 percent in the 1999 budget
from 1998 and a slight increase of 0.3 percent in the 2000 budget.
</P>
<P>
The deficit will be 160 million dinars (424 million dollars)
for the two years.
</P>
<P>
Revenues are estimated at 566 million dinars (1.68 billion
dollars) in 1999 and 572 million (1.7 billion dollars) in 2000, a
drop of 10 percent and 9 percent respectively as against 1998.
</P>
<P>
But non-oil earnings and assistance are estimated to reach 306
million dinars (908 million dollars) in 1999 and 316 million (937
million dollars) in 2000, an increase of 14 percent and 18 percent
respectively compared with 1998.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Minister of Manpower and Immigration Ahmed
el-Amawi has received a report from the Egyptian labour office in
Abu Dhabi, United Arab Emirates (UAE), defining available job
opportunities for the Egyptian work force in the UAE.
</P>
<P>
Engineers and workers for construction and agriculture are most
needed besides teachers, pharmacists, X-ray doctors, nurses and
university professors, Egyptian Arabic-language newspaper Alam Al
Yom reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the workers with expertise and foreign languages are
preferred.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- The World Bank has announced a 4 million dollars loan
to Morocco to improve the utilization of agricultural land and
exploitation of natural mountain resources.
</P>
<P>
The Alam Al Yom reported Wednesday that the project also
includes programs for improving living conditions and
income of the residents in these areas.
</P>
<P>
The project is considered an important change in the bank's
dealing with environmental issues and natural resources.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the World Bank has also announced a loan of 66
million dollars to Morocco to upgrade services in public
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Petroleum Minister Hamdi Al-Banbi has
disclosed that Egypt's capacity in oil refining will rise from 30
million tonnes to 35 million by the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
Egypt consumes 2 million tonnes of benzine a year, 85 percent
of which is unleaded, he said, adding that the target is to have
all kinds of benzine used in Egypt unleaded by the year 2000 to
diminish pollution, Egyptian Arabic newspaper Al Akhbar reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Al-Banbi said that 8.6 billion Egyptian pounds (2.53 billion
dollars), largely from banks, international companies and private
sector, will be invested in the near future in the petroleum
exploitation in the western desert. 
</P>
</TEXT>
