<HEADLINE> Over 500,000 Angolan Children Registered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Official sources in Angola
announced here Wednesday that over 500,000 children under 17
years old had been registered since the launching of free birth
registration in the southern African country in June this year.
</P>
<P>
According to Laurinda Perreira, coordinator for the national
birth registration campaign, the registration aided by the United
Nations Childrens' Foundation, is focused on street boys and war
orphans in a bid to offer better assistance to the children and
have their rights better protected.
</P>
<P>
Due to over two decades of civil war, she said, many residents
became refugees, the highest number being over three million
which was one third of the total population.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, most children born at this time were not formally
registered. Even now their nationality are not clear.
</P>
<P>
Perreira referred to the campaign as "positive", however, she
was quick to note that the recent escalation of armed conflicts
in certain areas since the second half of this year have hampered
the registration work so that the campaign could not conclude on
December 31 as originally scheduled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
