<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: HK's External Relations Ever Expanding After Handover (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) has not only maintained its existing
external contacts, but also expanded its external relations since
its return to China last year.
</P>
<P>
The continued development of the SAR's external relations since
July 1, 1997, is proof of the successful implementation of the
"one country, two systems" principle in the SAR's external
affairs, observers say.
</P>
<P>
The HKSAR government has sent its officials to attend, as
members of Chinese government delegations or on its own in the
name of "Hong Kong, China", more than 80 international
conferences.
</P>
<P>
It has also successfully hosted a number of large-scale
international conferences in Hong Kong. With its unprecedented new
identity, HKSAR has been more active on the arena of multilateral
affairs.
</P>
<P>
Foreign warships have continued to come to Hong Kong for
stopovers and recreations, and foreign VIP planes and military
aircraft have continued to land or fly over the territory. This
shows fully that Hong Kong remains very much the same open city of
self-confidence after the handover.
</P>
<P>
Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa has paid visits to 10 countries,
including Singapore, Malaysia, the United States, the United
Kingdom, France and Australia. Many other senior officials of the
SAR government have also had frequent overseas visits for exchange
of professional opinions.
</P>
<P>
The high-level protocol arrangements they enjoyed and the
importance attached to their visits are something officials of the
British Hong Kong government had never experienced before.
</P>
<P>
After the Sino-British Joint Declaration became effective in
1985, the Chinese and British sides started to discuss, based on
the Chinese government's post-1997 policies towards Hong Kong,
arrangements for the transitional period. It was at that time that
Hong Kong's external relations began to witness major changes.
</P>
<P>
Before July 1, 1997, Hong Kong's external relations were the
direct responsibility of the British government.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side agreed subsequently that the British Hong Kong
 government be authorized to negotiate separately bilateral
agreements in such important areas as civil aviation and surrender
of fugitive offenders. These policies pursued by the Chinese
government opened up new areas for Hong Kong's external relations.
</P>
<P>
Many countries have attached great importance to developing
their relations with HKSAR, regarding it as a major part of their
overall relations with China.
</P>
<P>
The heads of state of the United States, Romania, the
Philippines and Norway, vice-president of South Africa, prime
ministers of Britain and France, and many other foreign
dignitaries have visited Hong Kong or come here to attend
international conferences.
</P>
<P>
Before the handover, however, no foreign heads of state or
government, except that of Britain, paid official visits to Hong
Kong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: HK's External Relations Ever Expanding After Handover (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An SAR Government official commented that the current status of
the SAR's external relations is "unprecedented."
</P>
<P>
Being responsible for handling foreign affairs relating to the SAR
which are the responsibilities of the Central People's Government,
the Commissioner's Office of the Chinese Foreign Ministry has
served as a channel of communication between the Central People's
Government and the SAR government.
</P>
<P>
After the handover, the Commissioner's Office tackled issues
concerning the SAR's external relations "with a prudent and
unconventional approach" on the basis of the actual conditions and
in the best interests of Hong Kong with a view to implementing the
"one country, two countries" concept and promoting Hong Kong's
long-term prosperity and stability, an official at the office
said.
</P>
<P>
Since July 1, 1997, the office has issued exequaturs to
consuls-general and honorary consuls representing 13 countries and
consulted views of the HKSAR Government on 32 consular post
nominations submitted by foreign states.
</P>
<P>
The Commissioner's Office has handled and granted, upon the
approval of the Central People's Government, diplomatic clearance
for port-calls to 90 warships and for landing or flying over Hong
Kong to 143 foreign military aircraft and VIP planes.
</P>
<P>
The Office has also coordinated as necessary the arrangements
for overseas visits by the chief executive and other senior
officials of the SAR Government and visits to Hong Kong by foreign
state and government leaders.
</P>
<P>
The Office broke the conventions by permitting the expatriate
officials to attend international conferences as members of the
Chinese delegations and to speak separately in the name of "Hong
Kong, China." Such flexible arrangements are welcomed both by the
HKSAR government and the international community.
</P>
<P>
Another example is that the Central People's Government has,
based on its confidence and trust in the SAR Government, given the
latter a free hand to decide on the chief executive's overseas
visits and on proposals for visits to Hong Kong by foreign state
and government leaders.
</P>
<P>
During the overseas visits by the chief executive and other
senior SAR Government officials, the Commissioner's Office and the
Chinese missions abroad have rendered necessary protocol
arrangements and assistance, but have stayed away from official
talks and other formal activities.
</P>
<P>
When U.S. President Clinton visited Hong Kong in early July
this year, Commissioner Ma Yuzhen attended upon invitation the
welcoming banquet and President Clinton's public address and went
to the airport to see Clinton off.
</P>
<P>
Apart from these, the commissioner did not participate in any
other activities, neither the meeting between President Clinton
and SAR Government officials, nor the one between Clinton and
members of the Legislative Council. This is yet another
demonstration of the "one country, two systems" principle in
protocol arrangements.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Speeding Cameras to Operate for HK Police Next January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 30 (Xinhua) -- A round-the-clock automatic
camera system set up beside the main expressways on some spots in
the New Territories of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(SAR) will be operative next January 15 to further strengthen
anti-speeding enforcement action.
</P>
<P>
The "Speed Enforcement Camera System" was launched at a joint
press briefing here on Wednesday by Traffic Police and the
Transport Department.
</P>
<P>
Senior Superintendent, Traffic, New Territories North (T/NTN),
Allan Wong Sak-pang, said a total of 10 designated spots deemed to
be suitable for the installation of the cameras, have been
selected.
</P>
<P>
Wong said the main thrust of the system was a 24-hour radar
speeding detector which worked automatically.
</P>
<P>
"The equipment is more efficient and cost-effective when
compared with manual operation. The all-weather speeding detector
helps remind the drivers to observe the speed limits on respective
roads," Wong said.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking at the press briefing, Senior Engineer of the
Transport Department Tai Seung-kun said the system consisted of a
total of 10 camera housings which had been installed at
approximate 1.5 to two kilometers interval along the road.
</P>
<P>
Two speed enforcement cameras, each carrying a roll of film with
800 frames, will be mounted on these camera housings on a random
basis. The cameras will record vehicles engaged in a speed
exceeding the limits.
</P>
<P>
New traffic signs bearing the wording 'Enforcement Camera' had
been installed along the road to remind drivers of the system in
advance.
</P>
<P>
And the films will be retrieved daily by traffic police
officers for photo-finishing process. Police will contact the
vehicle owner in writing for information on the driver if
recordings on the film indicated that the vehicle has exceeded the
speed limits. Fixed penalty tickets will then be issued to the
drivers.
</P>
<P>
Police together with the Transport Department had studied the
3-million-HK-dollar (384,600 U.S. dollars) project since June
last year.
</P>
<P>
With the new device in place, road accidents attributed to
speeding can be expected to be further reduced and the safety of
road users ensured, Wong added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
