<HEADLINE> Marathon Man Rousseau Announce Retirement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Belgian marathon runner and
former track star Vincent Rousseau announced his retirement here
on Wednesday after his absence in the last two seasons.
</P>
<P>
The 36-year-old, the 1994 European 10,000 meters silver
medallist and who also won the 1994 Rotterdam marathon before
injury forced him out off the last two seasons.
</P>
<P>
He decided to retire after he was injured again when making a
comeback in November.
</P>
<P>
"I am retiring because all the injuries have stopped me from
getting my rhythm back and it has exhausted me," Rousseau said.
</P>
<P>
His personal best over the marathon, in Berlin in 1995, stood
at two hours seven minutes 20 seconds the second-fastest mark
that year. Rousseau became known as an eccentric who often
refused to run marathons because it was either too hot or too
cold. 
</P>
</TEXT>
