<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mortality Rate High Among Iraqi Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 30 (Xinhua) -- More than 6,300 Iraqi
children under the age of five and nearly 2,600 elderly people
died in November from various diseases as a result of the over
eight-year-old sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Statistics issued Wednesday by the Iraqi Health Ministry show
that 1,631 children died of diarrhoea, 2,419 of pneumonia and
respiratory diseases and 2,319 of malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
In November 1989 before the United Nations imposed the
embargo on Iraq, only 258 children died of various diseases.
</P>
<P>
The figures also show that 579 elderly people died of heart
disease and hypertension, 413 of diabetes and 1,592 of malignant
neoplasms.
</P>
<P>
Only 422 elderly people died in the same month of 1989.
</P>
<P>
So far in 1998, the mortality of Iraqi children under five have
risen to 62,790 while that of elderly people have climbed to
57,102, the statistics show.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has declared that over 1 million children and elderly
people have died of various curable diseases since the imposition
of the U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. imposed crippling sanctions on Iraq following its
1990 invasion of Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
