<HEADLINE> China Working on Macao Garrison Law (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Relevant departments in
China's central government are now drafting a law on stationing
People's Liberation Army (PLA) troops in Macao after China resumes
the exercise of sovereignty over Macao on December 20, 1999,
according to a report in a local newspaper.
</P>
<P>
"This law, which will be drafted on the basis of the 'one
country, two systems' principle, and relevant stipulations in the
Basic Law of the Macao Special Administrative Region (SAR), can
provide a solid legal basis for the central government to send an
army garrison to Macao after its smooth return to the motherland,"
said a signed article published recently in the "China National
Defense Daily."
</P>
<P>
The article, titled "The Return of Macao and the Macao
Garrison", noted that the anticipated Macao garrison law will take
into account the social characteristics of Macao and the necessity
for stationing troops there, drawing experience from the existing
Law on Stationing Troops in the Hong Kong SAR, which came into
effect on July 1, 1997 when China resumed its exercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"The law is expected to make explicit stipulations on issues
such as the duties of the Macao garrison, the relationship between
the garrison and the SAR government, the garrison's liabilities
and discipline, and the judicial administration over the garrison
personnel," the article said.
</P>
</TEXT>
