<HEADLINE> Philippine President on Compromise With Marcos Family </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada said Wednesday that the government is willing to negotiate
with the Marcos family for a compromise over its alleged
ill-gotten wealth, but such a deal should be truly beneficial to
the Filipino people.
</P>
<P>
The government will continue to pursue its cases against the
Marcoses in court as the proposed negotiations merely aim to speed
up the wealth-recovery process, Estrada told reporters here.
</P>
<P>
"Well, as I told you, we'll be willing to negotiate as long as
it will be for the advantage of our government and our people. As
long as it will benefit our people, okay, we will. As long as it
is legal, as long as it is advantageous to the government, we
will," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, Estrada said, he has yet to communicate directly with
former First Lady Imelda Marcos, saying he has not seen her "for
several months" now.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Estrada said the government is willing to enter into a
compromise agreement with the Marcoses as long as the results of
the deal would prove beneficial to the people, especially the
poor.
</P>
<P>
The former first lady told a press conference Tuesday that she
was ready to strike a compromise deal with the government after
asking the graft court to dismiss the forfeiture case against her
for alleged lack of evidence.
</P>
<P>
But Estrada said that the government is gathering more evidence
to further strengthen its forfeiture case against her.
</P>
<P>
"The government failed to get any solid evidence in the last 12
years, so we will still continue gathering evidence, but we will
also negotiate with them to put on the fast-track the settlement
of this issue," he said.
</P>
<P>
Former president Ferdinand Marcos was toppled in a "people's
Power Revolution" in 1986 and died in Hawaii three years later.
But only part of his alleged ill-gotten wealth has been recovered
by the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
