<HEADLINE> China Working on Macao Garrison Law (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On September 18, during the third plenary session of the
Preparatory Committee for the Macao SAR, the Chinese government
formally announced its decision to send garrison troops to Macao
after it becomes the country's second SAR.
</P>
<P>
The article notes that stationing PLA troops in Macao will be
an important sign of China's resumption of exercise of sovereignty
over Macao, and a major step for maintaining social stability and
economic prosperity in Macao following its return.
</P>
<P>
"Nothing other than stationing troops can reflect China's
sovereignty over its own territory," it quoted late Chinese leader
Deng Xiaoping as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law of the Macao SAR, which calls for the central
government to take charge of Macao's defense affairs, also
provides a direct legal foundation for stationing troops in Macao,
it added.
</P>
<P>
According to the draft law, the article said, the PLA Macao
garrison will only be responsible for Macao's defense and will not
intervene in any affairs within the scope of self-government
granted to the SAR. All garrison personnel must abide by both
China's national laws and the laws of the SAR.
</P>
<P>
The draft law will also clearly stipulate that the central
government shall cover all the expenses of the Macao garrison, it
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
