<HEADLINE> Venture Capital Industry Extends in Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's venture capital
industry raised 1.1 billion Singapore dollars (about 667 million
U.S dollars) in the first ten months of 1998, surging up 230
percent compared with that of the same period of 1997, the
country's Economic Development Board (EDB) announced in a press
release Wednesday
</P>
<P>
EDB said Singapore's venture capital, with more than 70 active
international and home grown fund management groups involved, now
manages a total of 8.8 billion Singapore dollars (about 5.3
billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
According to EDB, the Singapore venture capital community in
1998 put in 600 million Singapore dollars (about 364 million U.S.
dollars) for investments, of which Singapore attracted 140 million
Singapore dollars (about 85 million U.S. dollars). The figure
resenting a quarter of the total, is comparable to the amount of
142 million Singapore dollars (about 86 million U.S. dollars)
invested in other ASEAN countries.
</P>
<P>
EDB said companies backed by venture capital accounted for six
out of the 17 companies listed in the Stock Exchange of Singapore
in the first ten months of this year, bringing to almost 60 the
total number of locally listed companies backed by the venture
capital.
</P>
<P>
EDB also noted that start-up companies continued to receive
significant support from the venture capital industry,
constituting almost half of the 35 Singapore companies that
received venture capital funding.
</P>
<P>
Technology oriented companies received the strongest support
from venture capital support, EDB said, adding the information
technology industry received the highest number of investment,
with 13 companies enjoying 16 million Singapore dollars (about 9.7
million U.S. dollars) of the fund invested in Singapore. 
</P>
</TEXT>
