<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: HK Signs Record Number of Agreements With Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong, as authorized by
the Central People's Government, has signed 23 agreements with 17
countries in six areas since its return to China on July 1 last
year.
</P>
<P>
Seventy-six more bilateral agreements are being negotiated with
42 countries, official sources said.
</P>
<P>
These areas involve air services, surrender of fugitive
offenders, air transit, investment protection, transfer of
sentenced persons and mutual legal assistance.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Hong Kong has concluded accords with foreign states
and made administrative arrangements within the limits of its
autonomy in accordance with the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
"It is unprecedented that Hong Kong has signed so many
agreements with foreign countries in a short span of 500 days,"
said Ma Yuzhen, commissioner of the Chinese Foreign Ministry in
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR).
</P>
<P>
"This shows the determination of the Central People's
Government to resolutely implement the principle of 'one country,
two systems' and the Basic Law, and to maintain Hong Kong's broad
contacts with the international community," Ma said.
</P>
<P>
Before the handover, the number of bilateral agreements that
Hong Kong signed with foreign countries averaged less than 10 a
year.
</P>
<P>
As a special administrative region of China, Hong Kong
continues to maintain and develop wide-ranging contacts with the
international community.
</P>
<P>
According to relevant stipulations of the Basic Law, the SAR
government, authorized by the Central People's Government, can
negotiate and sign agreements with foreign countries on the
above-mentioned six areas.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Hong Kong is also authorized by the Central People's
Government to negotiate agreements or arrangements with foreign
countries and regions on the granting of visa-free access.
</P>
<P>
Now 56 countries and regions have agreed to grant visa-free
access to HKSAR passport holders.
</P>
<P>
But, in the course of more than 100 years before 1985,
Britain's bilateral agreements were applied to Hong Kong and the
latter had no power to conclude agreements with foreign partners
in these six areas.
</P>
<P>
The situation changed fundamentally only after the Sino-British
Joint Declaration on the Question of Hong Kong became effective in
1985.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the Chinese government's policies on Hong
Kong to be implemented after 1997, the Chinese side agreed that
Britain could authorize the British Hong Kong government to
negotiate separately bilateral agreements with foreign countries
in such areas as air services and surrender of fugitive
offenders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's Largest Canyon Narrower Than Thought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The Yarlung Zangbo canyon on
southwest China's Tibet-Qinghai Plateau, claimed by Chinese
scientists as the world's longest and deepest canyon, is narrower
than formerly believed, said several scientists here today, who
have hiked the canyon recently.
</P>
<P>
"The narrowest point, discovered for the first time in the
heart area of the canyon, is only 35 meters wide," said Gao
Dengyi, executive vice-chairman of the China Association of
Scientific Expeditions.
</P>
<P>
"Formerly, it was believed that the narrowest point in the
canyon was 78 meters," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he gave no details on the exact length and depth of
the canyon, data which they attempted to obtain during their
expedition from October 19 to December 10.
</P>
<P>
"The width at the narrowest point of the canyon is easy to get,
but the length and depth of the canyon needs further verification
by the State Bureau of Surveying and Mapping," said Gao.
</P>
<P>
A group of Chinese scientists made careful surveys of the
canyon in 1994, and determined its length to be 496.3 kilometers
and its average depth more than 5,000 meters, which would make it
the world's longest and deepest canyon.
</P>
<P>
Before that, the Grand Canyon in the southwestern United States
and the Canyon of Cerro Colca in Peru had been considered the
longest and deepest canyons in the world, respectively.
</P>
<P>
However, because of technical problems, the data gathered by
Chinese scientists in the early 1990s are now considered not
completely accurate. So one of the important tasks for the
expedition team this time was measuring the canyon with the Global
Positioning System and other modern scientific methods, and
updating the relevant data.
</P>
<P>
The results of the survey soon will be announced by the State
Bureau of Surveying and Mapping, according to Gao.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
