<HEADLINE> Beijing Clamps Down on Car Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- In a bid to cut the high
pollution levels in the Chinese capital, Beijing Municipal
Government is to issue special environmental protection licences
for autos whose tail gas emissions have reached the set standard
for discharge, said Wang Guotao, vice-mayor of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The new system will be introduced early in 1999 and Wang said
that the authorities will also ban cars which do not meet the
required emission levels especially when air quality exceeds the
normally acceptable pollution ratio.
</P>
<P>
This year the municipal government has taken 18 severe measures
to combat the serious air pollution in China's capital, eight of
which are aimed a reducing tail gas discharges from autos,
considered to be one of the main reasons for air pollution.
</P>
<P>
The measures taken so far include:
</P>
<P>
Insisting that all autos which have not reached the national
standards be taken off the road and destroyed.
</P>
<P>
Improving the monitoring of tail gas discharges.
</P>
<P>
Extending the areas prohibiting the use of trucks during
daytime.
</P>
<P>
Prohibiting the use of buses, and vehicles involved in
sanitation and waste collection if their tail gases do not reach
the lower standard for discharges.
</P>
<P>
As an ongoing regulation, from now on automobile manufacturers
selling products in Beijing will have to establish tail gas
control stations using national standards.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government will also improve the monitoring of
new vehicles for anti-pollution features from January 1 1999 as
well.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
