<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Lower Telecom Fees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- China is planning to
significantly lower telecommunications service fees, according to
a joint hearing held here today by the Ministry of Information
Industry (MII) and the State Development Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
According to a news release from the two-day hearing which
concludes today, the MII has put forward a plan to lower fees for
leased telephone lines and international telephone calls, and
raise fees for local calls and postal services.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the general level of overall charges for
telecommunication and postal services will drop significantly,
the news release said.
</P>
<P>
The public hearing was the first held by the MII since it was
set up in March. Among the more than 50 participants at the
hearing were representatives from users, operators, government
institutes, non-government communities, provincial price and post
and telecommunications administrations, and economists and other
experts.
</P>
<P>
"This hearing is a very positive trial," a MII official said,
adding that it's purpose is to upgrade the payment system of
China's post and telecommunications industry to international
standards.
</P>
<P>
China has repeatedly adjusted this payment system over the past
few years, and in December 1996 it lowered the fees for telephone
installation, leased lines and international telephone calls and
integrated fee scales for long distance call within the
country. At the same time, fees for postal services and local
telephone calls have been raised.
</P>
<P>
The MII will amend the fee adjustment plan after the hearing,
and hand it's decision over to the State Council for approval in
the near future.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
