<HEADLINE> Nigerian Labor Congress Satisfied With Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The Nigeria Labor Congress
(NLC) has announced the suspension of its 12-day ultimatum,
saying that it was satisfied with the government's assurance of
reviewing oil price increase.
</P>
<P>
The announcement followed a meeting between government
officials and labor leaders in capital Abuja Tuesday, The
Guardian newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A decision was made at the meeting to set up two committees
which will discuss and make recommendations on the increase
in oil pump price and the issue of minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the NLC issued the ultimatum which expires on
January 4, 1999, urging the Nigerian government to reverse the
price increase of petroleum products or face the wrath of workers
nationwide after oil marketers increased the official price of
petroleum from 11 Naira (about 0.13 U.S. Dollars) to 25 Naira per
liter.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Nigerian Labor and Productivity Minister
Emmanuel Udogu told reporters in Abuja that the government has
asked the workers in the country to look at their demands with
national interest.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that low revenue expected from
the 1999 budget pegged on nine Dollars per barrel of oil, was
cited by the government as the reason for the inevitable oil
price hike last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
