<HEADLINE> China Top of World's Grapefruit Table </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- China now leads the world in
the growing and output of grapefruit, producing 920,000 tons in
1998.
</P>
<P>
Since the late 1980s, China has developed several varieties of
grapefruit and set up six centers for growing the sweet fruit in
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, as well as in Guangdong, Hunan,
and Zhejiang provinces.
</P>
<P>
The county of Jiangyong in Hunan Province, south of the
Yangtze River, is considered the country's best growing area for
citrus fruits generally. It aims to generate 1.6 billion yuan in
annual grapefruit sales by increasing its planting areas from the
current 6,600 ha. to 13,300 ha. by the early part of the next
century.
</P>
<P>
This was announced at the 5th national grapefruit scientific
and research cooperation meeting held recently in Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
Grapefruit is now native to China, and other countries and
regions in Southeast Asia, having been introduced as long as 4,000
years ago.
</P>
<P>
There is great potential to exploit the export of grapefruit in
China, according to experts, as it only accounted for 7.47 percent
of the country's total citrus fruit output in 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
