<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Cracks Down on Industrial Polluters in Taihu Lake Valley </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- China has shut down 143
factories with serious pollution problems in the Taihu Lake valley
because of their tardiness in introducing anti-pollution measures.
</P>
<P>
All factories with a daily waste water emission of 100 tons
have to meet state standards before January 1, 1999, the State
Council has decreed.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics show that 878 factories, or nearly 85 percent
of the 1,035 major polluters in the region have installed water
treatment facilities and met the standards.
</P>
<P>
"Fourteen factories are still installing the safeguards," said
an official with the State Environmental Protection Administration
(SEPA). "However, they will be forced to stop production if they
fail to finish within the next two days.
</P>
<P>
"All polluters have to meet emission standards before the
deadline, or be shut down," said Xie Zhenhua, director of the SEPA.
</P>
<P>
Key SEPA officials are working in the Taihu Lake valley
supervising the fight against pollution and carrying out round the
clock spot checks.
</P>
<P>
A number of factories have been severely penalized in the past
few days for stopping the waste water treatment.
</P>
<P>
The SEPA has asked environmental departments in the region to
strictly enforce the law and cut water and electricity supplies to
closed factories.
</P>
<P>
The administration will carry out a major inspection around the
valley on the New Year's eve, joining forces with officials from
the State Development Planning Commission, the State Economic and
Trade Commission, the Ministry of Supervision, the Ministry of
Finance, the Ministry of Construction and the Ministry of Water
Resources.
</P>
<P>
Tough measures will be taken against offenders on the night,
officials insist pointing out that the results of the checks will
also be publicized.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
