<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Approves Additional Funding for Ethiopia's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU),
which is funding Ethiopia's 266-km-long Addis Ababa-Modjo-Awassa
road project, has approved an additional cost of 3.96 million
U.S. Dollars for the project.
</P>
<P>
To fulfil the new strategy of the road project, EU has agreed
an additional commitment of 9.55 percent on the original
contract, bringing the new total cost of the project to 45.42
million U.S. Dollars, Ethiopian English weekly The Reporter
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The new strategy to completely reconstruct the Addis
Ababa-Modjo section of the Addis Ababa-Modjo-Awassa road project
was suggested by the Ethiopian Road Authority.
</P>
<P>
In line with the new strategy, the existing pavement is being
milled to a depth of 20 centimeters and reshaped and compacted to
provide a sub-base for the new pavement.
</P>
<P>
Under the original project contract which was singed in September
1997, the work for the Addis Ababa-Modjo section of the road
concerned mainly the repair of the existing pavement.
</P>
<P>
The contract includes repairs of distressed areas and potholes
as well as the reconstruction of areas with base failure
conditions, filling of cracks and the provision of an overlay.
</P>
<P>
A detailed road condition survey carried out by the Ethiopian
Road Authority in March/April 1998 showed that the condition of
the road was so bad that it needed a complete reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
The EU-financed Addis Ababa-Modjo-Awassa road is the most
important highway in Ethiopia, connecting the southern and
eastern regions and the ports of Assab and Djibouti to the
capital and the rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
The project includes the rehabilitation of 266-km asphalt road
to be undertaken in two sections. The first section involves the
reconstruction of a 61-km road from Addis Ababa to
Modjo, while the second section covers the rehabilitation of the
205-km road from Modjo to Awassa.
</P>
<P>
The project will be completed in 40 months under the new
strategy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong Retains Investment Magnetism (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Guangdong Province continues
to retain its position as China's most attractive target for
investments in spite of emerging unfavorable factors such as
rising land and labor costs.
</P>
<P>
The south China province, the pioneer of the nation's reform
and opening policies, approved more than 13,000 overseas-funded
projects during the January-October period this year.
</P>
<P>
Since 1978 the year the country introduced the reform and
opening-up policy, Guangdong has taken full advantage of the
reform and opening policies, as well as its favorable geographical
location.
</P>
<P>
The province has consummated over 200,000 contract for overseas
investments worth 81.1 billion US dollars over the past two
decades, or close to 36 percent of the national total for the
period.
</P>
<P>
The nationwide deepening of the reform and opening has helped
the province to extend great effort to improve its market system
and accelerate the introduction of international standards for
local business activities, according to Cai Fuchun, director of
the Guangdong Foreign Economic and Trade Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
William Bowles, president of IBM China, attributes the
company's expansion in Guangdong to the strong local material and
technological base, export-oriented economy, vast market potential
and large contingent of professionals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
