<HEADLINE> Guangdong Retains Investment Magnetism (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bowles expressed satisfaction with the investment environment
in the province and noted that IBM built a second plant earlier
this year at a cost of 20 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The province has spent over 190 billion yuan on highway,
railway, airport, and telecommunications construction over the
past two decades. The province's transportation and
telecommunications network includes railways stretching over 2,000
km and highways running 90,000 km, as well as 10 airports and 14
million telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
Cai predicted that Guangdong will continue to witness
sustained, stable and rapid economic development which will
increase the influx of overseas investments in coming years.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the local economic growth rate will quite likely
edge down to 10 percent over the next few years, but added that
province still expects to attract annual overseas investments of
10 billion US dollars. The per capita income for urbanites will
continue to grow by six percent annually, with the growth rate for
rural residents leveling off at around five percent, according to
Cai.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong will place priority on attracting investments and
advanced management expertise from multinationals and
international consortiums.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong will continue to pursue comprehensive policies to
encourage overseas investments in basic industries, agricultural
modernization and the hi-tech sectors in particular.  
</P>
</TEXT>
