<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique to Greatly Increase Aquatic Export to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 30 (Xinhua) -- With the European Union
opening up its market from January 31, 1999, Mozambican aquatic
exports to Europe will see a great increase, Mozambican Minister
of Agriculture and Fisheries Carlos do Rosario has said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said here Tuesday that a European Union
delegation to Mozambique early this month conducted a on-the-spot
investigation and was satisfied with the quality of the aquatic
products of the southern African country.
</P>
<P>
Carlos do Rosario said that his country is
expected to become one of the major exporters of fresh fish to
Europe in 1999.
</P>
<P>
From January to September in 1998, Mozambique earned some 62
million U.S. Dollars from its export of fish, shrimps and prawns
and 60 percent of the export went to Europe, Wednesday's Noticias
newspaper quoted the minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
For 1997, the aquatic exports earned Mozambique some 99.1
million Dollars, accounting for about 44 percent of its gross
domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
The E.U. decided to ban import of aquatic products from the
poor southern African country after cholera broke out in
Mozambique in the late half of last year and early this year.
</P>
<P>
Although the E.U. lifted the ban in June, it did not fully
open its markets to the Mozambican fishery products.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican government took measures in August to
strengthen monitoring and inspection on fishery products and
hygienic situation and meanwhile demanded that the E.U. remove
its ban on the Mozambican products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
