<HEADLINE> Warm Winter Pushes Up Death Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The warmest winter in Beijing
for 50 years has taken a heavy toll amongst the old resulting in a
record number of deaths, mostly due to a flu epidemic which has
raged in the capital and around northern China for weeks.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics reveal that more than 1800 people have been
cremated in Beijing's Babaoshan Crematorium since December 5th, a
40 percent increase over the same period last year with often more
than 130 bodies a day being handled.
</P>
<P>
More than 80 percent were aged above 60, most of whom died of
pneumonia, respiratory and heart diseases.
</P>
<P>
Beijing is enjoying unusually mild winter weather and since
mid-December the temperature was a full three degrees higher over
ten consecutive days than last year. But it has helped fuel the
flu outbreak which has seen hospitals crowded with four times the
number of patients than is usual for this time of the year.
</P>
<P>
The freak weather has also threatened plans for an ice lantern
festival in the mountainous Yanqing County in Northern Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Its a traditional winter must-see in Beijing when ice blocks
are carved into lanterns with light bulbs fitted inside.
</P>
<P>
But sculptors have been forced to work after dusk to take
advantage of the colder temperature and organizers now say the
festival will have to be postponed.
</P>
<P>
However, they are confident of the weather returning to its
normal cold spell in the New Year when the festival will be held.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
