<HEADLINE> Philippine President Signs Into Law 1999 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada Wednesday signed into law the 1999 General Appropriations
Act (GAA), authorizing the government to spend the
579.5-billion-peso (145 billion U.S. dollars) pro-poor budget.
</P>
<P>
In his speech before signing the budget into law here, Estrada
said that the early enactment of the budget measure will enable
the Philippine economy to register a real growth rate of 3-3.5
percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
He called for prudence and judiciousness in the use of
government financial resources in order to respond to the people's
demand for the most productive and beneficial services.
</P>
<P>
Of the 579.5 billion pesos, nearly 68 percent are dedicated to
key social services, the development of agriculture and priority
infrastructure for rural areas, Estrada said.
</P>
<P>
With the approved expenditure program, he said, his
administration will be able to give the economy the push it needs
to get it out of the danger zone of the Asian economic crisis and
set firm the path of steady growth.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said that the government will play a more active role
in the economy by introducing a number of budgetary reforms in the
coming year in order to make the implementation of the budget more
transparent and potent for stirring economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The budget was approved by the House of Representatives and the
Senate earlier this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
