<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Businesses Urged to Solve Y2K Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Australian businesses were
Wednesday urged by an official group to make New Year resolutions
to eliminate the Y2K, or millennium bug, which potentially poses
the biggest threat to their survival.
</P>
<P>
Graeme Inchley, chief executive officer of the Australian
federal government initiated Y2K Industry Program, said not enough
businesses were taking the bug seriously even though there was
only a year to go before it struck.
</P>
<P>
His group has compiled a 10-point checklist of New Year
resolutions for businesses to deal with the issue.
</P>
<P>
"Results from recent Australian Bureau of Statistics research
indicate that over 40 percent of businesses have yet to undertake
any preparation for the year 2000 date change program; this number
is far too high," Inchley said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Inchley echoed concerns earlier this year of Australian
Communications Minister Richard Alston that many small businesses
saw Y2K as a problem for larger concerns.
</P>
<P>
"A company with only five employees has a high risk of failure
if its critical systems are not checked for year 2000 compliance,"
he warned.
</P>
<P>
The checklist urges businesses to ensure they are prepared for
the bug by taking preparations, including contingency plans for
systems failure, checks on suppliers to ensure their systems were
sound, and sharing information with other companies.
</P>
<P>
It also suggests businesses check the Y2K register on the
Internet to find Y2K compliant vendor products and services, check
with the Australian Taxation Office about tax deductions for Y2K
preparations and lobby industry groups for help. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
