<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Lifts Ban on External Borrowing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has
decided to lift the ban on external borrowing imposed last year
by the former administration of Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
The Chief of General Staff of the Nigerian armed forces,
Okhari Akhigbe made the remarks Tuesday in Abuja while briefing
reporters on the outcome of a joint meeting of the Provisional
Ruling Council and the National Council of State at which the
1999 budget was approved.
</P>
<P>
The Abacha government announced last July that it would not
borrow from any foreign countries or organizations until it had
paid all its external debt.
</P>
<P>
"We want to remove all barriers that would not allow for the
flexibility in government even now that we are moving to
democratic government," Akhigbe said.
</P>
<P>
"If government finds the need to borrow, then it should be
able to do so," Akhigbe said, adding that "if there is a reason
for you to borrow money to provide water, this is a capital
project. This is part of the things you can never run away from."
</P>
<P>
But he said that the government will control any situation
that will lead to excessive external borrowing.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's current external debt stands between 28 to 34
billion U.S. Dollars, according to the estimate of different
sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
