<HEADLINE> Nigeria's 1999 Budget Pegs Oil Price at $9 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has
approved the 1999 budget, pegging it on a benchmark of between
nine and 10 U.S. Dollars per barrel of crude oil, about eight
Dollars less than 1998 budget's 17 Dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
Following a joint meeting of the Provisional Ruling Council
and the National Council of States held in capital Abuja Tuesday,
Chief of General Staff of the armed forces, Mike Akhigbe, said
that the budget will reduce some capital projects and cut down on
the expected expenditure for the 1999 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the difficult issues, particularly the problems
of deficit, were adequately discussed by the two councils which
met twice last week, media reports said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We have been able to reduce it (deficit) to a manageable
level," said Akhigbe, adding that in this regard, "we tried to
avoid a situation whereby we create problem of dwindling
economy."
</P>
<P>
The nine to 10 Dollars oil peg is based on the fact that the
falling international crude oil price will not slide below nine
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
If the crude oil price slid below nine Dollars, Akhigbe said,
the government has put in place a contingency plan to ensure that
it will not compromise the living standards of Nigerians.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Head of State General Abdulsalam Abubakar is expected
to brief the press ahead of the budget broadcast which is
probably on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria is one of the major oil producing countries in the
world, exporting about two million barrels of crude oil every day
and about 70 percent of its budget revenue depends on oil export.
</P>
<P>
In view of the falling price of crude oil in the international
market, Nigeria can be expected to realize 7.45 billion Dollars
this year from oil export, as against 10.89 billion and 11.99
billion Dollars in 1996 and 1997 respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
