<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Model Village Prospers Under Market Economy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, December 30 (Xinhua) -- For almost twenty years in the
1960s and 70s, Dazhai Village in north China's Shanxi Province was
held up as one of the country's key model communities and was
visited by more than 25,000 foreigners from 134 countries and
regions including heads of state.
</P>
<P>
After the late chairman Mao Zedong in 1964 urged the whole
country to follow Dazhai's example as a working agricultural
unit, more than nine million Chinese visited it to get ideas and
inspiration.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1960s, the villagers of Dazhai relied on their
collective actions to move mountains, fill in gullies and create
farmland from the hills and copses of their region, turning it
into a prosperous place.
</P>
<P>
Today, Dazhai appears very tranquil on the surface and only a
museum at the foot of the hill reminds people of their agrarian
past.
</P>
<P>
Jia Haiwen, the village's 37-year-old accountant, explained
that it seems quiet because most abled-bodied people now work in
village-run industrial enterprises or are engaged in a wide range
of working activities in places outside the village, leaving only
the old and the young at home.
</P>
<P>
With a population of 500, Dazhai Village now boasts seven
enterprises, including a garment-making company, a cement company,
and a distillery, with fixed assets of 54 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
"Our village-run enterprises also employ quite a number of
people from neighboring villages," said Jia.
</P>
<P>
Adults now only spend their spare time tending the fields which
are easily tilled and maintained mechanically, and are charged 150
yuan (about 18 U.S. dollars) service commission by the village
administration for one hectare of land worked.
</P>
<P>
The net income of local residents has increased from the 700
yuan of a decade ago to today's 2,700 yuan. Leisure goods such as
radios and hi-fis as well as VCD players, are common in many
homes, bringing modern ways to the once rural, mountainous village
life. Old people also receive monthly pensions ranging from 50
yuan to 90 yuan from village funds.
</P>
<P>
This transformation was led by Guo Fenglian, who can be seen in
photographs of the time wearing a Mao-suit and wearing her hair in
two plaits at the back. In others she is depicted as a
militia woman and holds a rifle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
