<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Employers Try to Solve Housing Problem in Silicon Valley </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Employers of high-tech
companies in the Silicon Valley of the United States have
established a new trust fund to help the homeless and those with
low income find places to live in, officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Silicon Valley's housing problem has arisen along with
high-tech boom, said Carl Guardino, president of Silicon Valley
Manufacturing Group, who represents employers of about 250,000
high-tech workers.
</P>
<P>
A median priced home sold for 320,000 U.S. dollars in 1996 in
the area, nearly tripled the average.
</P>
<P>
Rents have jumped 30 percent in the past two years in Silicon
Valley. Only about one third of the area's families can afford a
house while about 1,200 poor people sleep outside every night
because shelters are filled.
</P>
<P>
"The fund is a good example of the spirit of Silicon Valley.
We don't just whine about the problem. We work together to solve
it," Guardino said, adding that the companies plan to raise 20
million dollars in two years for their new Housing Trust Fund.
</P>
<P>
Those funds will be leveraged to bring in another 80 million
dollars in government grants and loans, according to Leslee
Coleman,executive director of the American Electronics
Association's Bay Area Council.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, organizers announced they had just received
150,000 dollars from the John S. and James L. Knight Foundation,
while the Packard Foundation recently donated 180,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Local government, Santa Clara County, has also contributed 2
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Community Foundation development director Susan Luenberger
said their challenge now is to get the highly paid executives in
the region to share their wealth.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the top 100 executives in Silicon Valley earned
an average of 6.9 million dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"The money is like funny money to them, and they often are
quite young and don't have much experience with philanthropy,"
said Luenberger. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
