<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hydropower Plant in Southwest China Goes on Stream </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The first 300,000-kw
generating unit installed at Tianshengqiao first-tier hydropower
station on the Hongshui River was connected to the local power
grid in southwest China's Guizhou Province Monday.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the second 500-kv super high-voltage power
transmission line from Tianshengqiao to Guangzhou, capital of
south China's Guangdong Province, also came into service.
</P>
<P>
The Tianshengqiao hydropower station is one of a series planned
to be built on the Hongshui River. It is jointly financed between
the State, Guangdong and Guizhou provinces and the Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region with a total investment of 10.352 billion yuan,
including the use of 19.6 billion Japanese yen from the
International Cooperation Fund of Japan.
</P>
<P>
Four 300,000-kw generating units will be installed at the
station which will be able to generate 5.23 billion kwh of
electricity annually on completion in June 2000.
</P>
<P>
In another development, four 220,000-kw generating units
installed at Tianshengqiao's second-tier hydropower station
downstream have been linked to local power grids. By 2000, two
other 220,000-kw generating units will be added to this station,
making the Tianshengqiao area a major power source for
transmitting electricity from western to eastern parts of the
country.
</P>
<P>
While stepping up construction of hydropower stations, China
has completed four power transmission lines and has been
constructing two other power transmission lines.
</P>
<P>
The State is also to make further investments in constructing
three new large power stations in cooperation with the local
governments of southwest China.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, the power grids of southwestern China will
have reached a power transmission capacity of four million kw, 3.5
million kw of which will be used to transmit power to Guangdong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
