<HEADLINE> Philippines Releases More Social Security Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The Social Security System
(SSS), the only government agency in the Philippines mandated to
collect and manage insurance funds for private sector workers,
released 25.2 billion pesos (625 million U.S. dollars) in benefits
for its 19 million members in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The amount was 23 percent higher than the previous year's
disbursement of benefit funds, the Philippine News Agency reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
SSS Chairman Carlos A. Arellano was quoted by the agency as
saying that of the total benefit disbursement, 96 percent went to
social security benefits while 4 percent went to employees'
compensation benefits.
</P>
<P>
The higher disbursement of benefit funds could be attributed to
the strengthening of SSS programs, a move which Arellano
immediately embarked on after he was appointed SSS chief by
President Joseph Estrada, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Supporting the president's pro-poor stance, Arellano moved to
increase the benefits of SSS members without requiring additional
contributions from them, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
