<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unions Have Increasing Role in Foreign-Funded Firms (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
However, not all overseas-funded businesses have experienced
the same situation as Mr. Saito.
</P>
<P>
W. Keith Lomason II, general manager of the Shanghai Lomason
Automotive Seating Systems Co., Ltd., confesses that he worried
during the first years of the Sino-U.S. joint venture.
</P>
<P>
"But after three years, I now understand that trade unions in
China are not like those in North America who are always in
confrontation with the management," he said.
</P>
<P>
The American entrepreneur said that in China, the unions
encourage the staff to be enthusiastic and even help develop
production techniques and quotas.
</P>
<P>
The general manager has been personally involved in some union
activities. With his support, the workers have created roof-top
gardens as well as opening their own laundry, gymnasium, library
and meeting room.
</P>
<P>
However, the trade unions have never forgotten their real
responsibilities. For example, union leaders angrily intervened
when two women working at the Hotel Nikko Shanghai, a solely owned
Japanese venture, were given an illegal and rough body-search.
</P>
<P>
Later, the Japanese general manager was forced to publish a
letter regretting the incident and his salary was cut. Three other
lower-ranking Japanese managers were dismissed for their part in
the incident and the two Chinese women were each paid 8,000 yuan
in compensation.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Xianglin, a law expert with the Shanghai Federation of
Workers' Unions, said that the unions in overseas-funded
businesses in China do not just look after the welfare of the
workers or engage in struggle with the leaders.
</P>
<P>
"They work to safeguard the lawful rights and interests of the
staff, negotiate when differences occur between workers and
management, and help establish a stable relationship between the
two sides; all to help develop the enterprise in a healthy way,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Unions in China have built a bridge for communication,
understanding and cooperation between the two sides in business,
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
