<HEADLINE> 95,000 Mozambicans Benefit from Danish Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 30 (Xinhua) -- More than 95,000 Mozambicans
benefited from a Danish emergency aid program in 1998, according
to an annual report of the office of the Danish People to People
Relief Association in Maputo.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's Noticias newspaper quoted the report as saying
that the 150-ton aid goods it has collected include food, seeds
and used clothes imported from other countries.
</P>
<P>
The report issued by the Danish association Tuesday said
that five provinces, namely Maputo, Gaza, Manica, Sofala and
Tete, are recipients of the aid.
</P>
<P>
The used clothes came from some European countries including
Switzerland, Austria, Spain and Denmark.
</P>
<P>
The emergency aid program implemented by the Danish relief
group was designed to help those vulnerable to wars and natural
disasters by donating to them used clothes, food and seeds.
</P>
<P>
The program was also funded by the Austrian government and the
United States Agency for International Development.
</P>
<P>
The Danish relief group also employs the income from the sales
of the used clothes to offer health care to the victims
traumatized during the 16-year-old civil war in Mozambique and
provide education to the vulnerable people.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, some 91,000 Mozambicans got 126 tons of used clothes
from the aid program.
</P>
<P>
An aid for children program was implemented by the Danish
relief group in Mozambique's central Manica province. For last
year, children from 2,206 families benefited from the program in
both education and health care. 
</P>
</TEXT>
