<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Set to Expand Development of Township Firms (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, December 30 (Xinhua) -- A senior official with the
Ministry of Agriculture recently told Xinhua that plans have been
worked out to call for accelerating the development of township
enterprises to alleviate poverty in central and western China.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Yongtao, director of the ministry's Township Enterprise
Bureau, said the development of township enterprises will promote
economic growth in the regions.
</P>
<P>
He said the Chinese government will provide training over the
next two years to raise the qualifications of the personnel
working for township enterprises and upgrade the technological
level of local industries.
</P>
<P>
The regions will also enjoy favorable financial policies,
including discounted annual interest on loans of approximately
one billion yuan, said Jiang.
</P>
<P>
The output value for China's township enterprises currently
accounts for close to a third of the country's gross domestic
product (GDP), with rural enterprises accounting for close to 67
percent of the total rural value-added.
</P>
<P>
Township enterprises in central and western China, areas which
are home to 60 percent of the country's total population, account
for 40 percent of the gross output value of township enterprises
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Experts attribute the relatively poor economic performance in
the region to the underdevelopment of township enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The regions are also home to the bulk of China's
poverty-stricken population. One reason cited for the large
number of needy people is that rural enterprises in western areas
provide only eight percent of total income for farmers, compared
to some 80 percent in east China.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, the local governments in central and western
provinces have listed the development of township enterprises
high on their agendas. Northwest China's Gansu Province listed
related efforts as a top priority which will represent a
fundamental step in economic revitalization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Set to Expand Development of Township Firms (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The central government has actively promoted economic
cooperation between rural enterprises in eastern coastal and
midwestern regions since 1995 in order to tap vast potential of
abundant natural and labor resources in the latter. The effort
has also centered on introducing advanced technology and
equipment from eastern China.
</P>
<P>
The regions have drawn investments of over 40 billion yuans
over the past three years, with over 40,000 cooperative projects
involving total investments of 75 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Township enterprises in the regions have also experienced
various problems during the course of rapid development.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that the rapid growth of township
enterprises has generated a large demand of capital which cannot
be satisfied simply by the capacity of enterprises to accumulate
funds, central government allocations or investments from eastern
companies.
</P>
<P>
The fact that banks have been reluctant to shoulder the
responsibility has made it difficult for small rural enterprises
to obtain loans.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the outdated management concepts of entrepreneurs
and incompetence of employees have also hindered the development
of rural industry in central and western regions.
</P>
<P>
Sun Longshan, a high-ranking official with the Provincial Tow
nship Enterprise Bureau in east China's Jiangsu Province, said
that some cooperative projects have faced difficulties when left
to the management of local enterprises the regions. He noted that
eastern companies have in many cases been forced to dispatch p
ersonnel to solve related problems.
</P>
<P>
"Economic growth in poverty-stricken regions will depend on
the training and qualifications of local personnel," according to
Sun.
</P>
<P>
In addition, underdeveloped transportation infrastructure has
caused overseas companies and eastern enterprises to hesitate
when considering investments in the regions. Related companies
unacquainted with the regions have also exhibited uncertainty
about existing economic policies.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government is fully cognizant of the situation and
has stressed the implementation of all favorable policies. The
government has also introduced measures to attract investment and
train personnel in government branches and enterprises, as well
as to accelerate infrastructure construction in central and
western areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0157 </DOCNO>
