<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Rise on Wall Street Gains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
maintained its positive mood Wednesday but declined to fully take
on board a sharp rise on Wall Street Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index picked up 15.8 points to
close at 2784.2.
</P>
<P>
"We are up following a stronger performance on Wall Street
overnight in light turnover," Morgan Stockbroking's Simon Reed
said.
</P>
<P>
Light trade was again the order of the day ahead of Thursday's
half day session and Friday's new year holiday.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index rose 29 points to 5011.1 while the
all resources index added 4.9 points to 960.8.
</P>
<P>
Australia's diversified miner BHP lost four cents to 11.80
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector was stronger as the Commonwealth Bank of
Australia rose 32 cents to 23.00 Australian dollars, ANZ bank
picked up five cents to 10.55 Australian dollars and Westpac bank
lifted 6.4 cents to 10.773 Australian dollars. National Australia
Bank was the only one of the country's four major banks to lose
ground, falling 0.7 of a cent to 24.40 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index rose despite a fall in the price of the precious
metal.
</P>
<P>
The sub-index was 15.5 points stronger at 1095.7 while the
price of gold bullion in Sydney was 40 U.S. cents softer from its
close Tuesday at 286.10 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary national turnover was 322.84 million shares traded
for 584.12 million U.S. dollars, with rising stocks outnumbering
falling stocks 452 to 414 and 351 stocks steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
