<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korean Consumer Prices Up 7.5 Percent in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Meanwhile, this year's inflation rate stood at 7.5 percent and
it was lower than the government expected. In 1997, it was 4.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
Through consultations with the International Monetary Fund
(IMF),the country originally predicted the inflation rate would
reach nine percent in the middle of this year, but it later
revised the downward inflation target.
</P>
<P>
The ministry attributed this year's high inflation to the
won's steep depreciation in the wake of the financial crisis
caused by corporate failures and bad loans of financial
institutions in late 1997 and on tax increases.
</P>
<P>
Due to the financial turmoil that brought down the won against
the U.S. dollar, consumer prices soared as import prices for
crude oil and other key materials surged.
</P>
<P>
However, consumer prices began stabilizing from the middle of
this year thanks to the won's appreciation.
</P>
<P>
"We expect inflation for the year of 1999 to remain at three
percent on average as both consumption and investment show
continuing stability," said a ministry spokesman.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting last November, South Korea and the IMF agreed to
contain the 1999 inflation below five percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
