<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: China Committed to Intellectual Property Protection (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Yu Zheng
</P>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- As certain parts of the world
experience economic chaos as the year draws to a close, China has
again stood out as the protector of intellectual property rights.
</P>
<P>
The world's most populous nation did not pay lip service to
this but made substantial progress in ensuring its success, even
though it only introduced the world standard for IP in the last
twenty years.
</P>
<P>
In April this year, the China Patent Office was upgraded to the
State Intellectual Property Office (SIPO), directly under the
highest executive body -- the State Council. Apart from its former
functions and powers, the SIPO is empowered to coordinate with
other countries on IP issues, such as copyright, inventions,
trademarks and patents.
</P>
<P>
Then, the Chinese government set up the first IP training
center in Beijing. SIPO officials hope that by attracting
international IP experts and scholars it will take the lead in the
Asian-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
Attending an international IP symposium in April in Beijing,
Francois Curchod, deputy director-general of the World
Intellectual Property Organization (WIPO), declared that China has
made "tremendous progress" in protecting intellectual property
rights.
</P>
<P>
"China has promoted a greater awareness of intellectual
property, and the WIPO intends to continue and enhance still close
cooperation with it," Curchod said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: China Committed to Intellectual Property Protection (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Since 1982, the state has introduced trademark, patent and
copyright laws as well as regulations for the protection of
computer software and instituted a law against unfair competition.
</P>
<P>
This year the SIPO also carried out nationwide spot checks on
288 patent agencies, including nine specializing in foreign
business, looking into their business operations, internal
discipline, financial audit and personnel training. It has
announced such checks will be held every two years and that those
agencies which don't reach the pre-set standards will receive a
warning or be banned from operating.
</P>
<P>
Currently there are 580 patent agencies, with more than 4,800
authorized agents in China.
</P>
<P>
In tandem with the new legislation Chinese enterprises have
also shown a greater awareness of IP protection. According to
statistics released by the SIPO, there has been an average 25
percent yearly growth of patent applications. Most of them have
come from a number of large, efficient and profitable industrial
enterprises. Coastal areas and economically-developed regions have
also taken the lead in these matters.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China has ensured the success of IP by enforcing
its laws strictly. Over the last six years, courts nationwide
handled 22,860 IP disputes, reaching verdicts on 21,830.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with Chinese law, and in agreement with
international procedure, the courts have increased the legal
protection of intellectual property rights for plagiarizism,
illegal copying and forgery as well as for breaches of contract.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: China Committed to Intellectual Property Protection (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The revised Criminal Law took effect in October 1997 and allows
for a three to seven year prison sentence for offenders.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the Supreme People's Court plans to set up a web site
on the Internet, providing information about various court
verdicts in IP cases.
</P>
<P>
In June, Chinese customs began its biggest ever crackdown on
copyright piracy, crushing more than 1.8 million smuggled compact
discs in Guangzhou. Since 1996, the authorities have shut down and
dismantled 64 VCD production lines throughout China.
</P>
<P>
Many countries have highly praised China's commitment to IP
protection. Lois Boland, an official with the US Patents and
Trademarks Office, said, "We have been happy with the progress in
China."
</P>
<P>
China did become involved in IP disputes with the United States
some years ago but a new report indicates that last year China had
taken the lead over most other countries in patent applications
and approval. The state has also cracked down heavily on
counterfeit goods and copyright piracy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chinese experts, senior U.S. trade officials and
representatives from world IP organizations conducted a live
interactive Worldnet dialogue about IP issues in July.
</P>
<P>
Michael Kirk, executive director of the American Intellectual
Property Law Association, said that the patent system has been in
effect for more than 200 years in the United States.
</P>
<P>
"Although China introduced such a system only two decades ago,
it has established a set of fairly good laws and regulations,"
added Kirk, a former U.S. Deputy Assistant Secretary of Commerce
and Deputy Commissioner of Patents and Trademarks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Passage of Securities Law Has Positive Impact on Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Xinhua Writer Qian Yuhong
</P>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- China's stock market reacted
poorly to the news of the passage of the nation's first Securities
Law with sliding stock prices and a slim turnover.
</P>
<P>
Although the two bourses in Shanghai and Shenzhen edged up
today to close at 1148 and 2952 points respectively, the stock
indices of the two markets had already slid more than ten percent
from six weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
However, the poor performance of the market is not apparently
dampening the enthusiasm of investors, who believe that the new
law will have a positive impact on the market in all aspects.
</P>
<P>
The law -- five years in the making and finally approved by the
National People's Congress, China's legislature, on Tuesday --
promises an airtight and comprehensive regulatory framework that
will rule out market irregularities and over-speculation, which
have severely hit individual investors over the past eight years.
</P>
<P>
"The markets have remained sluggish for six weeks in a row,
because the rumor about the passage of the Securities Law has been
driving great amount of illegal funds away from the market,"
explained Chen Jinling, research director with the Guotai
Securities Co. Ltd.
</P>
<P>
"Actually the current bearish market promises an easier path to
a rationalized market ruled by law in the future, and the passage
of the Securities Law will prove to be of great benefit in the
long run," stressed Chen.
</P>
<P>
Individual investors, who lost the most as a result of market
irregularities and over-speculation in the past, are expected to
gain a lot from the passage of the law, because such a law - in
any country - makes the interests of the individual investors a
priority to encourage their enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
China currently has 38 million stock investors, and individual
investors comprise more than 90 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Overspeculation, insider trading and the spreading of false
market rumors have long been plaguing China's stock market since
it was launched eight years ago, and sometimes the financial risks
have become so enormous that the government has been forced to
step in to cool the market down.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Weimin, 29 years old, said he is a firm believer in blue
chips but has lost more than 10,000 yuan in one year as a result
of the investment rationale.
</P>
<P>
"When blue chips are the favorite son on most mature stock
markets, they are dumped on China's market like hot potatoes,"
said Zhang, who is deeply concerned at the situation and
considering whether to sell his stocks at a loss.
</P>
<P>
Still, Zhang has hopes that the new law will help create fair
opportunities for all investors, promise high returns for
investors in companies with a good performance and potential and
thereby encourage rational stock-investing in the future.
</P>
<P>
Overseas comment about the passage of the Securities Law has
been positive and foreign observers believe it will break the
unending cycle of government intervention brought on by various
froms of trading irregularities and speculation, which has
dominated the eight-year history of the two bourses in Shanghai
and Shenzhen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Center for Economic Microcirculation Development Set up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The China Center for Economic
Microcirculation Development was set up in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
Comprising nearly one hundred scientists, economists and
government officials, the center plans to seek and establish a
sustainable development plan for China's rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The economic microcirculation theory, merges the inner
circulation patterns of organizations and focuses on solving the
inner problem so that the conditions of microcirculation of
regional economic and social development can be improved and
sustainable development realized.
</P>
<P>
The center will try to raise more funds to support the economic
development of poorer areas.
</P>
<P>
The economic microcirculation theory was first adopted in China
in 1995.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
