<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Train Fares to Go up Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzania Railways
Corporation (TRC) will increase its passenger train fares for
first and second class by a margin of 37 to 50 percent from the
beginning of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The fare hike, however, will not affect common people as it
specifically targets at first class and second class (sleeping)
passengers, according to TRC Acting Director General Isaac
Mwakajila.
</P>
<P>
TRC, owner of 1,560-mile Central Railway track, which runs
from Dar es Salaam on the Indian Ocean to the lakes of Victoria
and Tanganyika, has to hike its fare due to increase in its
operational costs, media reports said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Mwakajila was quoted as saying that passenger fare for first
class between Dar es Salaam to the Lake Tanganyika town of Kigoma
has been increased to 45,200 Shillings (about 67 U.S. Dollars)
from 30,200 Shillings.
</P>
<P>
First class passengers traveling from Dar es Salaam to Mwanza
town on the southern shore of Lake Victoria will have to pay
44,600 Shillings instead of 29,800 Shillings.
</P>
<P>
Fares for second class (sleeping) from
Dar es Salaam to Kigoma and Mwanza have respectively been raised
from 33,100 Shillings from 24,200 Shillings, and 32,600 Shillings
from 23,900 Shillings.
</P>
<P>
Third class, second class (sitting) and TRC ship passenger
fares remain unchanged, Mwakajila said.
</P>
<P>
TRC incurred a loss of 20 billion Shillings from devastating
floods caused by El Nino in late 1997 and early this year.
</P>
<P>
The last time TRC raised its fare was in Novermber 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Central Railway was built a century ago when Tanganyika
was still a colony of Germany. The other line Tanzania has is
the Tanzania-Zambia Railway. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Anticipate Increased Prawn Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists are
optimistic that applications of advanced technology will increase
China's prawn production.
</P>
<P>
Xiang Jianhai, a researcher with the Marine Research Institute
under the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences, noted that
technicians have helped prawn breeders in Guangdong, Hainan and
Guangxi provinces develop prawn farms which produce 400 kg of
prawns per mu.
</P>
<P>
Plastic film lining the bottom of breeding ponds facilitates
the removal of mud and saltwater is recycled through an enclosed
system.
</P>
<P>
China was the world's largest prawn producer in the late
1980s, with prawn farms covering 2.3 million mu achieving annual
output of between 200,000 and 300,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
However, a devastating virus which hit many farms in 1991
reduced the annual output to between 40,000-50,000 tons and China
has since been a major importer of related products.
</P>
<P>
Some farmers have either reduced the density of prawns or
delayed the birthing cycle in recent years to protect prawns from
diseases. However, related actions have dramatically reduced the
per mu output to under 50 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
Xiang said new technologies such as gender control will be
introduced in the near future and are expected to once again
become one of the world's major prawn producers.
</P>
<P>
Female prawns are bigger than males the same breed when
subjected to the same maturation environment. Scientists are thus
using gender control technology to hatch more female eggs.
</P>
<P>
Xiang pointed out that the female to male birth ratio for
prawns raised by the institute's scientists stands at 4:1, or a
level substantially higher than the 1:1 ratio for prawns bred in
natural environments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 08:18 </DATE_TIME>
