<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Hollywood Movie Angers S. African Moslems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The Moslem community in
South Africa is up in arms about Hollywood's latest movie "The
Siege", The Citizen newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the daily newspaper, the Moslems are to send a
letter demanding an apology from Ster Kinekor, South Africa's
largest cinema chain, due to its "insensitivity" in distributing
the "anti-Muslim/Islam" film.
</P>
<P>
The Hollywood production, starring Danzil Washington and
Annette Bening, is due for release on the South African circuit
early next year and apparently contains several "anti-Islam bias"
scenes.
</P>
<P>
According to a spokesman for Media Review Network, a watchdog
organization dealing with anti-Moslem practices and sentiments in
the media, the movie depicts Moslems as "bad terrorists."
</P>
<P>
"We want the film to be re-edited and all references to the
Koran, Islam and Muslims removed," said Anver Suliman Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We are demanding an apology to the Moslem community from Ster
Kinekor for its insensitivity," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to a script provided to an Islamic advocacy group,
the film is set in Brooklyn, New York, and involves a bombing
campaign by Moslems. This then prompts the American military to
declare martial law and carry out mass arrests of American
Moslems and Arab Americans.
</P>
<P>
"The Moslems see this as a blatant attempt to defame Islam,
the Moslems, once again," said Suliman.
</P>
<P>
Previews of the movie have depicted Moslems at prayer
juxtaposed with acts of violence.
</P>
<P>
He said as recent bombings in Cape Town, Nairobi, Dar es
Salaam, Afghanistan and the Sudan had shown, the constant
repetition of stereotypes and unacknowledged biases inevitably
led to prejudices and and outright violence against a minority
group.
</P>
<P>
Twentieth Century Fox, the production company involved in the
making of the film, however, said both the studio and the
filmmakers had had an ongoing and open dialog with representatives
of Arab communities since the production phase.
</P>
<P>
"Although the film was created primarily as entertainment,
another of its intentions was to raise awareness of issues such
as racism and prejudice," said Fox spokesperson, Florence Grace.
</P>
<P>
"We believe the film clearly accomplishes this and regret that
certain organizations have chosen to attack the film because its
antagonist is Muslim, rather than recognizing its broader themes
and positive intentions.
</P>
<P>
"In fact, this movie is not anti-Muslim or ant-Arab, but is
rather anti-prejudice and shows the tragic consequences of
racism," Grace said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unions Have Increasing Role in Overseas-Funded Firms (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 30 (Xinhua) --In many foreign countries,
trade unions are a big headache for management, but for
overseas-funded businesses in China it is a different matter
altogether.
</P>
<P>
Chinese unions work closely with top management to create a
good relationship and even help to promote the products.
</P>
<P>
For example, Lu Xiaomao, vice-chairman of the trade union at
the Shanghai Sharp Electronics Co., Ltd., a Sino-Japanese joint
venture, has been too busy to take a break because the year-end is
approaching.
</P>
<P>
Lu has just submitted to management 50 proposals from staff to
help improve production and now he has to select who will be
rewarded for their ideas.
</P>
<P>
"As a union leader, I have to safeguard the rights and
interests of the workers while helping the management by
encouraging the staff to make useful suggestions about factory
operations," said Lu.
</P>
<P>
"The better the company operates, the better the lifestyle of
the staff," he added.
</P>
<P>
Mitsuo Saito, general manager of Shanghai Sharp, said what has
impressed him most is that the trade union has often mobilized the
workers to promote the firm's products even during holidays. "The
union has become an inseparable part of the company," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Mr. Saito, his administration team works on a
fifty-fifty basis with the union to run the company and believes
this gives considerable strength.
</P>
<P>
A regular meeting between the management and the union is now
held once every month, compared with once every three months in
the past.
</P>
<P>
Union leaders have succeeded in persuading the management to
offer loans to staff who want to buy their own houses, reduce work
quotas in certain cases, and won additional pension payments for
retirement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
