<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro to Have Big Impact on Bangladesh: Business Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi economic players are
hopeful of a strong and stable Euro, the single European currency
which will make its debut in the world's financial market on
January 1, 1999, The New Nation daily reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
They expressed the hope while discussing the probable
guidelines and strategy to adjust the country's currency with the
Euro at a meeting of a five-member committee of the Bangladesh
Bank (BB), the central bank of the country, Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The committee, headed by the bank's deputy governor, will
submit a report to the bank's governor, suggesting the exchange
rate of the taka, Bangladesh's currency, with the Euro.
</P>
<P>
Since Europe as a region is Bangladesh's biggest trading
partner, the Euro will have a significant impact on the country's
economy and trade, according to committee members.
</P>
<P>
The Euro will be a very strong currency to compete and co-exist
with the U.S. dollar and the pound sterling, said President of the
Federation of Bangladesh Chambers of Commerce and Industries Abdul
Awal Mintoo.
</P>
<P>
The Euro will be a very stable currency, Foreign Investors'
Chamber of Commerce and Industry President A.K.M. Shamsuddin said.
</P>
<P>
Dhaka Metropolitan Chamber of Commerce and Industry President
Laila R. Kabir said the Euro will make Bangladesh's trade easier
with Europe, the major importer of Bangladesh's garments and
frozen food.
</P>
<P>
While fixing the currency rate of the taka with the Euro,
Bangladesh will have to watch what other regional countries do,
said professor of economics of the Dhaka University Dr. Abu Ahmed,
who is also a member of the committee.
</P>
<P>
"I'm not saying whether the Euro will be more powerful than the
dollar or not. But I hope it won't be a volatile one," he said,
adding that the Frankfurt-based European Central Bank is
determined to maintain the price stability of the Euro. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
