<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Disciplines Police Against Brutality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 30 (Xinhua)-- Tanzania has warned its
police of violation of human rights in the course of exercising their
duty, local media reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Director of Criminal Investigations of the Home Affairs
Ministry, Adadi Rajabu, stressed Tuesday that bestowed with vast powers,
the Police should know their limits.
</P>
<P>
Rajabu told a five-day seminar at the Kurasini Police College here
that the police authorities has launched a nation-wide
campaign against police brutality, vowing to take to book any police
officer violating human rights.
</P>
<P>
"We do not at all condone any abuse of human rights by members of
the police force. We condemn all sorts of such abuses or any form of
police brutality," he said.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, sponsored by the Irish government and United Nations
Development Program (UNDP), was attended by more than 30 participants
comprising police trainers, middle rank officers and operational
commanders.
</P>
<P>
Rajabu said that the police headquarters has a section which deals
with all complaints of police brutality from the citizens by taking
appropriate disciplinary actions.
</P>
<P>
"Rampant and wanton killings through misuse of firearms, torture
and other forms of harassment have all been reported," he disclosed.
"In some cases, police officers have been discharged from the force
and taken to court to answer criminal charges."
</P>
<P>
Rajabu said that the Tanzanian police force welcomes any
constructive criticism in a bid to mould them into a group of people
who observe the rule of law and uphold human rights.
</P>
<P>
"Endowed with very wide powers including those of arresting,
restraining, remanding and searching people, we are always in direct
confrontation with the rights and liberties of the people. Thus the
necessity of exercising maximum care so as not to infringe upon
peoples' rights unnecessarily," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Director restated the articles 25 to 28 of the Union
Constitution, saying that any policeman and policewoman is not allowed
to claim his or her rights and freedoms by violating their duties and
obligations.
</P>
<P>
Police sources said that beginning from next year, the police will
introduce special programs on human rights in the television and radio
broadcasting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pioneer of China's Enterprise Reform Never Gives Up (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, December 30 (Xinhua) -- One of China's reform
pioneers has now been honored in the northern tourist city of
Qinhuangdao with a huge portrait of himself hung outside the
headquarters of the Bu Xingsheng Clothing Group.
</P>
<P>
Indeed Bu Xingshen is the firm's 65 year-old president and
"Mr. Bu" the trademark attached to all products.
</P>
<P>
He hit the headlines in the 1980s for his bold management
reforms, but because China was not as that time fully prepared for
such reforms, his then business went into decline and Bu was
removed from his post.
</P>
<P>
Opinion has differed about the reasons for his ups and downs,
but business experts speak highly of Bu's pioneering work,
believing that it gave impetus to the first generation involved in
China's reform and opening-up drive.
</P>
<P>
"Bu failed initially because the time was not right and now he
has risen once again because a market-driven economy now exists in
China," said Yan Xuruo, a research fellow at the Zhejiang
Provincial Commission for Economic Restructuring.
</P>
<P>
The story began in 1981, when Bu, an ordinary tailor at the
Haiyan Shirt Factory, in Haiyan City of east China's Zhejiang
Province, was appointed as the factory's director by the city
government.
</P>
<P>
He soon broke decades-old traditions by experimenting with a
series of new management patterns such as the "system of
distribution according to work" and the "production in line with
demand", which were controversial at the time but boosted the
factory's output, resulting in enormous profits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pioneer of China's Enterprise Reform Never Gives Up (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The local media published many stories about his success and
this prompted central and local governments to introduce his
management style nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Soon people would say that it was more difficult to see Bu
Xinsheng than the mayor of the city. And so many people came to
Haiyan to learn his methods that only high-ranking officials were
allowed to visit him in person.
</P>
<P>
Yet the factory soon ran into difficulties, with debts
mounting, resulting in Bu's removal from his post in 1988.
</P>
<P>
Later, he went to work for other clothing factories in
Shanghai, Beijing and Liaoning Province in the northeast. Then in
1993, he was offered his present post by Zhang Bin, the firm's
owner. "I appreciate his initiative, and his popularity, of
course," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Bu has increased the capacity of the company by
acquiring several other firms and extending its scope of
operations to include both manufacturing and marketing/sales. Its
assets have surged from four million yuan to 120 million.
</P>
<P>
"It's much easier to run an enterprise nowadays as we have a
better business environment," the reform pioneer said. "I don't
have to waste 70 percent of my effort dealing with various
external interferences as in the past."
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years, Bu has transformed the private
company using modern business methods.
</P>
<P>
Although Bu is now a partner in the firm he declined to
disclose his yearly income. He said he has no plans to retire,
disclosing that his next goal is to turn "Bu Xinsheng" into an
internationally recognized brandname. Bu has also been busy
preparing for his company to go public. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
