<HEADLINE> 1998: Eventful Year for India's Capital Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Political uncertainty
remained the prime concern for the capital market throughout 1998
in India, The Observer of Business and Politics said here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Even though the market showed resilience, the fluid political
and economic situation in India and around the world continued to
throw up surprises, which is something market operators don't
like," the paper said.
</P>
<P>
"Hopes of a bullish market were always followed by moments of
despair throughout the year with the sensitive index of the Bombay
Stock Exchange (BSE) touching a high of 4,000 and crashing to as
low as 2,800 ruining small and medium investors," it said.
</P>
<P>
A bombshell was dropped, literally, in May when India exploded
five nuclear devices at Pokhran. Anticipating U.S. economic
sanctions, the market fell sharply by 300 points, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
"The nuclear tests also soured India's relations with Pakistan
and market operators were sure of a sizeable hike in the country's
defense budget," it further said.
</P>
<P>
"The June budget, however, disappointed the market, unleashing
a series of crashes which virtually drove the small investors
out," it said.
</P>
<P>
"A large number of investors are yet to recover from the sudden
crash during June-July which saw many losing their hard-earned
money overnight," it concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
