<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Businesses Permitted to Hold Commodity Exhibitions on Mainland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Foreign Trade
and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC) has decided to allow Taiwan
businesses to sponsor commodity exhibitions on the mainland in
order to improve cross-Straits trade relations.
</P>
<P>
Hu Chusheng, a spokesman for the (MOFTEC), announced the
decision on Wednesday. He said the decision was made in response
to increasing trade exchanges between the mainland and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
"The initiative once again fully demonstrates the mainland's
sincerity in promoting cross-Straits trade relations," said
Hu. "We hope that the Taiwan side will respond positively."
</P>
<P>
MOFTEC's management regulations on Taiwan-sponsored economic
and technological exhibitions held on the mainland list five
categories of related events -- cross-Straits economic and
technological exhibitions, export commodities fairs, and
international and national exhibitions involving the participation
of Taiwan businesses.
</P>
<P>
He said promulgation of the regulations is "of great
significance" to mark the forthcoming 20th anniversary of the
Message to Compatriots in Taiwan issued by the Standing Committee
of the National People's Congress (NPC).
</P>
<P>
Cross-Straits trade relations have witnessed remarkable
development following issuance of the aforementioned message to
conduct exchanges of mail services, trade, air and shipping
services, and implementation of the principles of peaceful
reunification and "one country, two systems".
</P>
<P>
To date, the cross-Straits trade volume has hit 134.7 billion
US dollars, including exports of 21.6 billion and imports of 113.1
billion dollars. Taiwan ranks as the mainland's fifth largest
trade partner.
</P>
<P>
Cross-Straits trade exchanges are currently conducted in the
form of trade, as well as Taiwan investments on the mainland and
technological, industrial, fishing and labor cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Hu stressed that the mainland sincerely hopes the Taiwan side
should cancel its restrictive policy and initiate direct exchanges
of mail, trade, air and shipping services at the earliest possible
date in order to concretely improve economic and trade
exchanges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
