<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thais Rush to Gold as Safe Haven </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The survey, conducted recently by the World Gold Council and
made public on Wednesday, said recession-related insecurity has
led to a "gold rush" in Asia as many people, particularly the
Thais, want to swap their unstable currency for the precious
metal.
</P>
<P>
The survey, which examined people's perceptions of gold before
and during the economic crisis, revealed that Asians' affinity for
gold had been significantly enhanced due to the economic
recession.
</P>
<P>
Gold in Thailand has been a traditional medium for investment.
It ranked highest among countries surveyed as the top asset in the
financial portfolios of respondents.
</P>
<P>
Selling of gold took place only as a last resort, with 79
percent of respondents stating they had sold gold to generate
urgent funds for the household. However, 85 percent said they had
no intention of selling more gold during the next six months.
</P>
<P>
Pongpan Pongsiribanyat, country manager of World Gold Council,
commented: "Traditionally, gold has always been a safe haven in
times of economic volatility. Thais have had a strong attachment
to gold but now as a result of their experiences of selling during
the crisis, their perception of the asset value of gold is much
stronger."
</P>
<P>
"Because of this combination of sentiment together with a new
awareness of gold's liquidity value, consumers have indicated a
strong intention to buy back most of the gold they 'dis-hoarded'.
Significant purchases are projected in the medium to long-term as
individuals rebuild their assets," he said.
</P>
<P>
The survey was conducted across Asian countries including
Thailand, Malaysia, South Korea and Indonesia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
