<HEADLINE> Thai PM Urged to Complete His Term </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The call came as the opposition was stepping up efforts to
launch a no-confidence motion against the coalition government,
coalition sources said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Chuan said earlier that the mission of his term was temporary
and if the economy picked up before 2000, he would dissolve the
House of Representatives and call a general election.
</P>
<P>
But key coalition figures urged Chuan to change his mind,
saying his stay in office would serve the nation's interests.
</P>
<P>
Korn Dabaransi, leader of the National Development Party, said
he saw nothing, even the upcoming no-confidence debate, that could
prevent the government from completing its term.
</P>
<P>
Korn, deputy premier and public health minister, said he did
not believe the opposition had enough teeth to make a serious
attack that would lead to major political changes.
</P>
<P>
He reasoned that if the government survived the no-confidence
debate expected in late January, no fresh censure motion could be
filed in the next parliamentary session, which, according to the
constitution, would be reserved for deliberation of bills only.
iversary
of His Majesty the King Bhumibol Adulyadej late next year, Korn
expected the political climate would be calm during that time.
</P>
<P>
"That meant we could survive another year so the prime
minister should stay on until 2000," he said.
</P>
<P>
Chuan, meanwhile, said in remarks published by Wednesday's
Bangkok Post that the cabinet ministers should be fully prepared
for the censure, particularly several key figures who were the
main target of the opposition.
</P>
<P>
He said he believed his ministers could clearly answer
opposition allegations during the censure debate.
</P>
<P>
He called on the Thai people to remain patient and continue
fighting to beat the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Chuan declined to say if the economy would register a growth
next year, but said its recovery would depend on global economic
situations.
</P>
<P>
He cited some positive signs like the stabilization of the baht
and the drop of inflation rate. But he said the liquidity crunch
and bad debts of financial institutions remained unsolved.
</P>
