<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Exports Up 0.9 Percent, Imports Down 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has recorded its worst
annual exports growth rate in a decade, the Vietnam Investment
Review reported in its latest issue, quoting the General
Department of Statistics Data.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 exports growth rate went up just 0.9 percent, while in
the same period, imports in all sectors plunged dramatically due
to tight restrictions on incoming goods, the English-language
weekly said.
</P>
<P>
The total value of exports in 1998 was 9.356 billion U.S.
dollars, some 8.3 percent lower than 10.2 billion U.S. dollars
which was officially targeted at the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
Over the last 12 months, Vietnam's imports were valued at 11.39
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The consequences of imports restriction policies and
short-term imports substitution measures were clearly demonstrated
by a confirmed 3 percent decline in Vietnam's total imports.
</P>
<P>
The finalized imports and exports figures left Vietnam with a
total end-of-year trade deficit of 2.034 billion U.S. dollars,
considerably lower than last year's deficit of 2.474 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
One Vietnamese trade official said the drop in the trade
deficit figure could lead to a mistaken perception that Vietnam
had begun to benefit from August's dong devaluation.
</P>
<P>
The truth of the matter, he determined, was that it totally
derived from the heavier restrictions on imports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
