<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Phnom Penh Casinos Ordered to Be Shut Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's Council of
Ministers has approved an order requiring all casinos in Phnom
Penh, capital of Cambodia, to close immediately except two that
have a six-month grace period.
</P>
<P>
The Naga Resorts Floating Casino and the Holiday International
Casino are allowed to operate at their current locations until
June 30, 1999, but after that they must relocate at least 200
kilometers away from Phnom Penh, the Cambodia Daily reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Council of Ministers also decided that casinos will not be
allowed in Siem Reap town.
</P>
<P>
The order, approved on Monday and effective immediately, also
bans Cambodians from gambling in casinos.
</P>
<P>
Government officials said they hope the ban will help reduce
crime, especially frequent abductions believed to be often related
to gaming debts.
</P>
<P>
"Casinos cause a lot of suffering. They are one of the main
causes of insecurity," a government official said.
</P>
<P>
The order was applauded by government officials as a positive
move in the fight against crime, but some conceded that closing
the casinos will be a difficult task. Some customers at the
Holiday Casino Tuesday said they agreed to the ban, and linked
gambling with crimes.
</P>
<P>
The government passed an anti-gambling law in January 1996,
which imposes maximum fines of 8,000 U.S. dollars and jail terms
of up to five years on owners of illegal gambling clubs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Extends Freeze on Government Personnel Wages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The financial crisis took
another toll on the Thai people as the government employees will
see no rise of their wages for another two years.
</P>
<P>
A Government House press release available Wednesday said the
Cabinet had approved the Finance Ministry's proposal to extend
austerity measures controlling spending on government personnel
till 2001.
</P>
<P>
Under the measures, there will be no establishment of new
agencies or expansion of existing ones until 2001, except for
those required by the constitution.
</P>
<P>
The salary scales, position allowances and welfare benefits
will be frozen.
</P>
<P>
The personnel administration will be limited to only what is
allowed in plans for increasing efficiency and spending cuts.
</P>
<P>
The austerity measures for 1998-1999 fiscal year, which ended
in September, have so far helped the government save some 8.16
billion baht (226.7 million U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
