<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua Top 10 Sports Events </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
1. France won the World Cup Soccer Finals for the first time
with a 3-0 victory over defending champion Brazil in the final.
A record 32 teams competed in and 64 matches were played in the
33-day French World Cup which attracted a record television
viewers of 40 billion.
</P>
<P>
2. Nearly 10,000 athletes, trainers and officials from 41
countries and regions took part in the 13th Asian Games in
Bangkok, Thailand. China topped the medal tally, followed by
South Korea in second place and Japan third. Thailand, still
haunted by Asian financial crisis, overcame many a difficulty to
ensure successful staging of the event.
</P>
<P>
3. At the Winter Olympic Games earlier this year, Germany
returned to the top spot in the medal chart with 12 golds. Norway
remained second with 10 golds and Russia, top finisher in the
1994 Lillehammer Games, was third with nine.
</P>
<P>
4. Doping scandals punctuated the year, with teams found
systematically administering banned drugs to their riders in the
Tour de France cycling race, and Italian soccer probing the use
of drugs which could boost players' stamina. In response, the
International Olympic Committee (IOC) proposed stricter measures
to counter the doping problem.
</P>
<P>
5. In December, veteran IOC official Marc Hodler made
allegations that potential hosts of some Olympic Games had been
offered IOC votes en bloc for cash by agents during the bidding
process. IOC President Juan Antonio Samaranch ordered an
investigation into the issue.
</P>
<P>
6. European soccer body UEFA revamped the continent's major
clubs competitions, expanding the Champions League to 32 teams
from 24, merging UEFA Cup with Cup Winners' Cup, and in compl
iance with the revenue division plan proposed by the top clubs.
The move foiled the attempts of setting up a Super League by an
Italian company and a dozen of European clubs, preventing the
break-up of European soccer.
</P>
<P>
7. The National Basketball Association lost this season's
games due to the work stoppage for the first time in 52 years,
following the lockout imposed by the owners in June. Owners and
players disagreed on the salary issues and negotiations turned
out to be fruitless.
</P>
<P>
8. Women's 100/200m world records holder Florence Griffith
Joyner died at home in September, sparking rumors that her death
was related to sports drugs. Forensic investigation showed an
epileptic seizure caused her suffocation to death.
</P>
<P>
9. Brazilian Joao Havelange, who had been FIFA President for
24 years, officially etired and was succeeded by former
Secretary-General Sepp Blatter, a winner over the other
candidate, UEFA President Johansson, in the election.
</P>
<P>
10. In order to draw more young people into the Olympic Move
ment, the inaugural World Youth Games was held in Moscow in July
as a result of proposal by IOC President Samaranch. The Games
staged 12 Olympic disciplines and was attended by 7,000 athletes
and guests from 140 delegations. The long-term objective of the
Games is to grow into a World Youth Olympic Games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
