<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Economic Rim Accelerates Cooperation (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Zhang Yuanyuan, a professor of economics at Jinan University,
said the fact that China has already regained sovereignty over
Hong Kong and will witness the return of Macao on December 20,
1999, does not necessarily mean the economic integration in the
south China region will be in place of itself.
</P>
<P>
"Working together to develop the South China Economic Rim and
forging a high-level economic alliance with help from concerned
local governments will not only be in line with the development
trend of economic globalization, but will also fundamentally help
solve existing problems and increase competitive advantages,"
according to Zhang.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong and Guangdong organized a joint cooperation
conference earlier this year to ensure the systemization of
government links. The conference becomes a regular one to be held
in every six months.
</P>
<P>
The development of a transregional network linking local
governments has proceeded smoothly with the installation of a new
fiber optic network serving Guangdong. The transregional network
will become operational in May 1999.
</P>
<P>
High-tech industries in the three areas have increased
cooperation, with related efforts including the establishment of a
Shenzhen-Hong Kong organization specializing in high-tech
industrial parks. Guangdong Governor Lu Ruihua recently noted that
the three areas will focus on high-tech cooperation during 1999.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong will allocate 20 billion yuan over the next coming
decade to construct ports of entry needed to facilitate exchanges
with Hong Kong and Macao.
</P>
<P>
A feasibility study on the Lingdingyang Bridge which will link
up Hong Kong, Guangdong and Macao is currently in progress. The
proposed project would provide south China with a highly efficient
transportation network of expressways, railways and deepwater
ports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
