<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Economy Grows 7.8 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- China's economy grew 7.8
percent in 1998 despite the impact of the Asian financial crisis,
the National Bureau of Statistics announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The nation has maintained a steady economic growth in the face
of "an extremely complicated international economic situation",
with gross domestic product totaling 7.9748 trillion yuan this
year, Ye Zhen, spokesman for the bureau, told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The outcome has basically met the central government's
projection of eight percent, Ye said.
</P>
<P>
China registered an 8.8 percent economic growth last year.
</P>
<P>
A trend of deflation has continued to pose pressure on the
economy this year, with the retail price index falling by 2.6
percent and the consumer price index down by 0.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to Ye, China's exports in 1998 are expected to reach
182 billion U.S. dollars worth, roughly matching last year's
level, while the amount of foreign investment actually used
totaled 54 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Ye said that the country's imports for 1998 are estimated at
137 billion U.S. dollars worth, down 3.8 percent from last year.
</P>
<P>
The trade surplus in 1998 will be about 45 billion
U.S. dollars, an increase of 4.7 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China's grain output this year reached 490 million
tons, matching last year's level.
</P>
<P>
Cotton output is expected to hit 4.33 million tons in 1998,
down 5.9 percent from last year, while output of oil-bearing crops
is expected to go up by five percent to 22.65 million tons.
</P>
<P>
As China's measures to boost domestic demand began to show
effects, the growth of industrial production picked up in the
middle of this year and sped up in recent months.
</P>
<P>
The bureau estimated that the industrial incremental value
increased by 8.8 percent on a yearly basis to 2.012 trillion yuan
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The value produced by state-owned industrial enterprises and
state-controlled firms was up 4.8 percent, while that of
collective industrial enterprises rose 8.8 percent and that of
industrial firms of other types jumped 13.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Ye told that investment in fixed assets in 1998 is expected to
reach 2.868 trillion yuan, up 15 percent from last year.
</P>
<P>
"Accelerated investment has been a major factor spurring
economic expansion," he said, adding that the increased investment
has been designed for infrastructure construction and the
development of basic industries, with priority given to central
and western China.
</P>
<P>
But the consumer market failed to keep pace with the
investment growth. The retail sales of consumer goods expanded by
6.8 percent to 2.9155 trillion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Ye said that the average per-capita income was 5,454 yuan for
urban residents and 2,150 yuan for rural residents this year, up
6.6 percent and four percent, respectively, in real terms.
</P>
<P>
"At present, the Chinese economy is still confronted with a
number of problems," he said, stressing that further measures
should be taken to overcome the problems such as sluggish
demand, poor performance of many enterprises and increasing
pressures in employment and re-employment.
</P>
<P>
China's industrial enterprises registered an estimated gross
profit of 118.4 billion yuan and a loss of 143.9 billion yuan in
the January-November period.
</P>
<P>
Ye said that China must continue to stimulate domestic demand,
step up the restructuring of state-owned enterprises and strive to
expand exports so as to maintain a sustained, rapid and sound
economic development in the next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
