<HEADLINE> Albanian Parliament Passes Fiscal 1999 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Albania's parliament on
Tuesday adopted the country's fiscal 1999 budget, stressing the
macro-economic stability, economic revival and continued
reduction of the financial deficit.
</P>
<P>
The budget, submitted by the government to the parliament, or
the People's Assembly, late last month for its review and
approval, was adopted after a day-long debate, with 102 votes in
favor and one abstention.
</P>
<P>
Under the budget, the country's total revenue in 1999 will be
111.7 billion leke (about 798 million U.S. dollars) and spending,
165.5 billion leke (1.1 billion U.S. dollars), producing a
deficit of 53.84 billion leke (313 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The budget projects a 19.4 percent revenue increase and a 15
percent spending increase. The budgetary deficit is confined to
below 9.8 percent of the Gross Domestic Product, as compared with
10.8 percent set by the fiscal 1998 budget, and domestic
financial deficit is expected to drop to 5.6 percent from 6.4
percent in fiscal 1998.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time that the parliament approved a budget pla
n of a next year before the end of the currency year.
</P>
<P>
Albanian Prime Minister Pandeli Majko, while presenting the
draft budget to the parliament, pledged to continue economic
restructuring in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
