<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Economic Rim Accelerates Cooperation (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Guangdong Province, Hong
Kong and Macao are expanding cooperation in order to accelerate
development of the South China Economic Rim (SCER).
</P>
<P>
The SCER, a high-level alliance formed by Guangdong Province,
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) and Macao,
focuses on production, services, management and
innovation. Experts note the SCER enables China to maintain close
ties with the international economic community.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. publication Business Week recently predicted that the
SCER's gross domestic product (GDP) will approximate the level of
France by the first half of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The HKSAR, an international financial, information and
transportation center, is in pursuit of "one country, two systems"
principle. Macao, which will become China's second special
administrative region in 1999, is a free trade port which enjoys
independent tariff status and extensive export quotas for the
European market. Guangdong has formed a strong contingent of
scientific, technological and research professionals, and enjoys
substantial influence in China's vast inland market,
</P>
<P>
Lin Jiang, director of the Hong Kong, Macao Research Center at
Zhongshan University in Guangdong Province, said the combined
advantages of Hong Kong, Macao and Guangdong will make the SCER an
importan force which will promote the integration of the Chinese
and international economies by early next century.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong, Macao and Guangdong have cooperated closely since
1978 when China introduced its reform and opening drive. The
cooperative effort includes the fact the a large number of
labor-intensive industrial enterprises have moved from Hong Kong
and Macao to Guangdong.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation over the past two decades has transformed Hong
Kong and Macao into "front shops" and Guangdong into "backyard
workshop", according to one researcher at the Chinese Academy of
Social Sciences (CASS).
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong and Macao manufacturing industries with low
production costs have enjoyed new opportunities for expansion,
while Guangdong has gained access to funding, technology and
management expertise. Participation in the division of labor has
promoted development in Guangdong and the province has witnessed
rapid economic expansion. The research fellow, a specialist on the
international economy, noted that Guangdong's gross economic
volume accounts for 10 percent of the national total. He added
that Guangdong is one China's most economically developed
areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
