<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Asiad Medalists Receive Cash Bonuses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 30 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government
has divided a 358 million rupiah (47,700 U.S. dollars) cash bonus
among the country's medalists from the 13th Asian Games in
Bangkok, the Jakarta Post reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
State Minister of Youth Affairs and Sports Agung Laksono and
Coordinating Minister for People's Welfare and Poverty
Eradication Haryono Suyono presented the bonus for six gold
medalists, 10 silver medalists, 11 bronze medalists and coaches
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Gold medalists were the Indonesian men's badminton team and
men's doubles pairing of Ricky Ahmad Subagja and Rexy Mainaky,
Yayuk Basuki (women's tennis singles), Oka Sulaksana (men's
windsurfing), Supriati Sutono (women's 5,000 meters track) and
Arief Taufan Syamsudin (men's karate).
</P>
<P>
Individual gold medalists received 15 million rupiah each.
Ricky and Rexy were awarded 11.5 million rupiah each and members
of the men's badminton team received 5 million rupiah each.
</P>
<P>
Each silver medalist took home 8 million rupiah and each
bronze medalist 5 million rupiah. Twenty-nine coaches were
awarded 2 million rupiah each.
</P>
<P>
Agung expressed satisfaction with the athletes' achievements
in the Asiad, held from December 6 to 20.
</P>
<P>
"Their performance was much better than four years ago when
we only won three golds from badminton. Now we have won six golds
from five sports. However, our ranking among the participating
countries and regions is still out of the top 10," he said after
presenting the bonus.
</P>
<P>
"I think our athletes still need to perform optimally. In the
future we expect them to win a competition by setting a new
record, either Asian or world record", he added.
</P>
<P>
Some of the athletes expressed appreciation for the bonuses.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very thankful to the government who tried hard to
provide bonuses during the economic crisis," said women's tennis
player Wynne Prakusya.
</P>
<P>
"This is great. I'll save the bonus to pay for my study,"
said Sinta Berliana Heru, who won a silver in taekwondo.
</P>
<P>
Supriati said her money would go to her parents. "I have
almost everything, a house, a family. The money will be used to
help my parents," she said.
</P>
<P>
Supriati, probably Indonesia's most surprising gold medalist,
said she wanted to qualify for the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
"I still have no plans about competing in which events next
year, but I hope I can qualify for the Olympics. I plan to retire
after that to have children," said Supriati, an Army sergeant.
</P>
</TEXT>
