<HEADLINE> Economic Group Boost Foreign Investments in Costa Rica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, December 29 (Xinhua) -- A rapid increase in foreign
investment has boosted Costa Rica's economic growth, the
Chile-based Latin America Economic Commission (Cepal) said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The commission said Costa Rica is now ranked the second fast
est economic growth country in the region, with a 5.5 percent
growth rate, following the Dominican Republic, which registered a
seven percent rate.
</P>
<P>
Cepal attributed the economic growth to a 16.3 percent
increase in foreign investment in 1998 over last year.
</P>
<P>
A Costa Rican state development agency said that 18 new
foreign companies had founded branches in the country this year.
As a result, exports grew by 13 percent this year, Cepal said.
</P>
<P>
Tourism also contributed to the growth with nearly 900 million
dollars channeled to the current account, much more than banana
or coffee exports.
</P>
<P>
Microchip exports for the U.S. company Intel, which started
this year in Costa Rica, also helped boost the trend.
</P>
<P>
Increasing foreign investment enabled the country to raise 80
million dollars to meet losses caused by higher interest rates.
</P>
</TEXT>
