<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The sixth meeting of the National People's Congress (NPC)
Standing Committee wound up in Beijing yesterday with the adoption
of the Securities Law and a supplementary provision to the Criminal
Law which stipulates a maximum sentence of life imprisonment for
major violations of foreign exchange regulations.
</P>
<P>
The Securities Law, which includes 214 articles in 12 chapters,
covers the issuance of stocks, purchases of listed companies,
securities trading and standards of conduct governing securities
companies.
</P>
<P>
The law will take effect as of July 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also approved the Law on Military Service,
which reduces the term of active duty of 3-4 years to 2 years,
will take effect immediately after promulgation.
</P>
<P>
-- The 150.7-kilometer Shanghai-Hangzhou expressway, absorbing
5.7 billion yuan of investment, become operational Tuesday
after five years construction.
</P>
<P>
It takes one hour and a half to drive from Shanghai, China's
leading industrial city, to Hangzhou, capital of east China's
Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- The per capita net income of Chinese farmers is expected to
increase three percent this year and four percent next year, said
Chen Yaobang, minister of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The specific figure will be announced by the State Statistics
Bureau today.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the country must optimize its agricultural
structure, deepen rural reform and improve the farming
environment to increase farmers' incomes and maintain stability.
</P>
<P>
-- A frontpage commentary hailed the adoption of China's first
Securities Law, saying the law will guarantee the sound
development of China's securities market.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- A former vice-governor of central China's Hubei Province has
been expelled from the Communist Party of China (CPC) for
corruption and serious violation of Party disciplines and laws,
the CPC Central Commission for Discipline Inspection announced in
Beijing yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The CPC Central Committee approved the decision to deprive Meng
Qingping of his party membership and Meng has already been
arrested by procuratorial organs.
</P>
<P>
-- Standard Chartered Bank's economists believe China's
economic growth will remain strong through 1999. The bank reported
the country's growth rate of close to 10 percent annually during
the past two decades is not overstated. 
</P>
