<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Economy to Grow 2.5 Percent Next Year: Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian economy is
expected to grow 2.5 percent next year despite the ongoing
economic and financial problems in other regions of the globe, a
Canadian bank predicted Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The bank's projected rate of growth is about half a percentage
point higher than that predicted by most other forecasters.
</P>
<P>
"The outlook for Canada is relatively positive for 1999, but
the risks are on the downside," Canadian Imperial Bank of
Commerce (CIBC) said in its latest economic report.
</P>
<P>
The strong U.S. economy has contributed significantly to the
performance of the Canadian economy in 1998.
</P>
<P>
"However, a softer U.S. economy next year will result in
reduced exports and a slowdown in Canada's economic growth," said
Canada's second largest commercial bank.
</P>
<P>
The structural problems in the economy, including a lack of
investment in research and development, internal trade barriers
and the need for improvement in education and training, have been
compounded by high government debt and taxes. "This has had a
corrosive effect on Canada's economic performance," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
"Canada needs to focus on measures to improve productivity
growth and global competitiveness ... Tax reductions and tax
reforms are necessary if Canadians are to see a more productive
economy with a strong dollar and a rising standard of living," it
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
