<HEADLINE> China's Economy Grows 7.8 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 30 (Xinhua) -- China's economy grew 7.8
percent in 1998 despite the impact of the Asian financial crisis,
the National Bureau of Statistics announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The nation has maintained a steady economic growth in the face
of "an extremely complicated international economic situation",
with gross domestic product totaling 7.9748 trillion yuan this
year, Ye Zhen, spokesman for the bureau, told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The outcome has basically met the central government's
projection of eight percent, Ye said.
</P>
<P>
China registered an 8.8 percent economic growth last year.
</P>
<P>
According to Ye, China's exports in 1998 are expected to reach
182 billion U.S. dollars worth, roughly matching last year's
level, while the amount of foreign investment actually used
totaled 54 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Ye said that the country's imports for 1998 are estimated at
137 billion U.S. dollars worth, down 3.8 percent from last year.
</P>
<P>
The trade surplus in 1998 will be about 45 billion
U.S. dollars, an increase of 4.7 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, China's grain output this year reached 490 million
tons, matching last year's level.
</P>
<P>
Cotton output is expected to hit 4.33 million tons in 1998,
down 5.9 percent from last year, while output of oil-bearing crops
is expected to go up by five percent to 22.65 million tons.
</P>
</TEXT>
