<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Fears Switch to Euro Means Less EU Farm Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 29 (Xinhua) -- A leading Italian farming
association on Tuesday expressed fears that the nation's switch
to Europe's single currency euro would reduce the real value of
the agriculture assistance distributed to Italy by the European
Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
The association, known as Coldiretti, estimated that the
Italian farmer would suffer an average cut of 35,860 lire (21.67
U.S. dollars) in the real value of EU aid next year because of
money conversion.
</P>
<P>
After January 1, 1999, institutional pricing and EU aid for
farmers will no longer be calculated in ECU -- the European
Currency Unit, but in euro, aiming in a long term to make the
European farm price support fairer and more efficient.
</P>
<P>
An ECU is equivalent to 2,030 lire while a euro between 1,930
and 1,950 lire.
</P>
<P>
The association said the most vulnerable sectors would be
grains, olive oil, fruits and vegetables, beef cattle and sheep.
</P>
<P>
European officials, acknowledging that the switch to euro will
result in aid cuts for some farmers, from 0.6 percent to 15
percent, have announced the establishment of an indirect
mechanism for compensating those hardest hit, which includes an
optional national co-financing equal to 50 percent of the lost
value from euro conversion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
