<HEADLINE> Fruitful WB-Funded Agricultural Development In Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, December 30 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Liaoning
Province has reaped fruitful results from the introduction of 75
million U.S. dollars in loans from the World Bank (WB) into local
agricultural development since 1984.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the province has produced 670 million kilos of
grain, 43.6 million kilos of vegetables, and more than 55 million
kilos of meat and aquatic products.
</P>
<P>
The use of the WB loans has helped the province reclaimed 7,000
hectares of paddy rice fields, transform 19,800 hectares of
non-irrigated land into irrigated farmland, set up 9,000
greenhouses for growing vegetables, raise 70,000 head of cattle,
and develop 14,666 hectares of pasture and tidal areas.
</P>
<P>
The entire plan for using WB loans for local agricultural
development involves a total of 85 million U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
