<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Security Council's Authority, A Must in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council Tuesday issued a presidential statement, once again
underlining the unshirkable and irreplaceable authority of the
United Nations in maintaining world peace and security.
</P>
<P>
The presidential statement, issued after the U.S.-led
unilateral military strikes on Iraq, was hammered out on the basis
of an open debate on "the maintenance of peace and security and
post-conflict peace-building."
</P>
<P>
Altogether, representatives from 22 countries, including China
and other 14 Security Council members, took the floor during the
debate, which was interrupted by the December 16 military action
against Iraq before its December 23 resumption.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on this, Ahmad Kamal, Pakistani permanent
representative to the United Nations, said, "It is ironic for us
to be addressing the role of the Security Council in the
maintenance of international peace and security at a time when the
ability of this Council to play it has been dealt a devastating
blow as a result of unilateral action undertaken without due
debate and authorization from the Council."
</P>
<P>
Qin Huasun, China's permanent representative to the United
Nations, said, "The world is undergoing profound changes at the
turn of the century. The desire for peace, stability and
development has become the shared understanding and common pursuit
of all Member States of this Organization."
</P>
<P>
"Maintaining international peace and security is the lofty
responsibility entrusted to the Council by the Charter of the
United Nations," Qin said. "The Council's primary responsibility
for maintaining international peace and security is both
unshirkable and irreplaceable."
</P>
<P>
"China is strongly opposed to any act of power politics that
unilaterally resorts to the use or threaten to the use of force in
international relations while circumventing the Council," he said.
</P>
<P>
Qin's remarks were echoed by his Russian counterpart, Sergey
Lavrov, who said, "The United Nations Charter, which assigns to
the Security Council primary responsibility for and a central role
in this very important area, remains the immutable and universal
legal basis for the maintenance of international peace and
security."
</P>
<P>
Lavrov voiced his concern about attempts to make it possible
for individual States or coalitions to use force or take
enforcement measures without the approval of the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"In this respect, the clearest such attempt can be seen in the
drawing up of a new strategic concept of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO)," he said.
</P>
<P>
NATO was reported to be considering an idea to transform the
Alliance into a leading international peacekeeping organization
whose actions, which would extend beyond the bounds of the
geographic zone for which the military bloc has responsibility,
would be taken solely on the basis of its own assessments and
decisions, thereby sidestepping the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"It is clear that we are talking about attempts to replace the
Charter-based functions and the prerogatives of the Security
Council with unilateral actions taken by regional mechanisms,
directly contravening the United Nations Charter," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Roselyn Odera, representative from the Kenyan
Mission to the United Nations, said that "primary responsibility
for the maintenance of international peace and security rests with
the Security Council."
</P>
<P>
Kamalesh Sharma, Indian permanent representative to the United
Nations, said that the attack on Iraq "has thrown up fundamental
problems and questions which must be addressed. We are faced with
a conflict resulting from unilateral action by some members of the
Council."
</P>
<P>
While greeting the impending arrival of the last year of this
century, the world found that none of the armed conflicts in
Afghanistan, Africa and the Balkans and the Iraqi crisis have been
solved, and the United Nations, including the 15-member Security
Council, are facing grave challenges of peace and security, global
economic and financial crisis in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
However, it is widely accepted that only by strict adherence to
the United Nations Charter and the upholding of the authority of
the Security Council, can the world, with the concerted assistance
of the international community, unsher into the next century a
developing, prosperous and stabilizing world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981230.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
