<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Sending Doctor to Yemen for Injured Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The United States is
sending a doctor to assist an American and two other Westerners
injured when Yemeni security forces attacked kidnappers holding 16
tourists, U.S. State Department officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
They said the American embassy in the capital San'a had
received preliminary reports on the incident from senior Yemeni
officials and were seeking further independent confirmation.
</P>
<P>
Among the 16 tourists kidnapped, three Britons and an
Australian were killed.
</P>
<P>
"No Americans have been reported among the dead.... The embassy
is sending a consular officer and a regional medical officer (a
doctor) from San'a to Aden (where the freed hostages were being
taken) as soon as they can get there," one of the officials said.
</P>
<P>
The 16 tourists -- 12 Britons, two Americans and two
Australians -- were kidnaped Monday while traveling by car on the
road between Habbas and Aden.
</P>
<P>
The Yemeni government has informed Washington that "it
undertook a rescue action" Tuesday and that at least three of the
hostages were killed during this action. 
</P>
</TEXT>
