<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Welcomes Cyprus' Decision on Russian Missiles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The United States Tuesday
welcomed Cyprus' decision not to bring Russian missiles to the
country and said the decision would ease tensions on the island.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome and support President (Glafcos) Clerides's decision
not to bring the S-300 missiles to Cyprus. We commend the
government of Cyprus for taking this important step to ease
tensions on the island," State Department spokesman Lee McClenny
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus announced earlier in the day that it would not take
possession of the Russian missiles and store them on the divided
island which Turkey has threatened to destroy and would negotiate
with Moscow for their deployment on Crete instead.
</P>
<P>
"This action will give important new impetus to Secretary
General (Kofi) Annan's September 30 initiative to reduce tensions
and promote a just and lasting settlement of the Cyprus dispute,"
McClenny said.
</P>
<P>
Washington "wholeheartedly supports the secretary general's
initiative and will take all necessary steps to support a
sustained effort to implement it," he added.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman urged all sides in the Cyprus dispute to work to
reduce tensions.
</P>
<P>
Another U.S. official said the missile decision means the
weapons "aren't going to Cyprus so now we can focus on the real
issues rather than on the side issues."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus ordered the Russian missiles in early 1997. Turkey,
which has occupied the northern third of the island since invading
it in 1974 after a brief Greek-inspired coup, immediately
threatened military action to prevent the missiles from arriving.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
