<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumer Confidence Steady: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Consumer confidence slipped
slightly in December in the United States, but was still
considered high, the New-York based Conference Board reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Board said its index of consumer confidence fell 0.3 point
to 126.1 from a revised 126.4 in November following a four month
retreat.
</P>
<P>
The Conference Board is a private research group complying the
monthly index based on the results of a nationwide survey.
</P>
<P>
It said consumers were moderately positive in December about
the current economic situation, but cautious about its performance
in coming months.
</P>
<P>
The index is a benchmark indicator as consumer spending
accounts for two-thirds of the U.S. economic activity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
