<HEADLINE> Security Council Calls for Cooperation Over Plane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council Tuesday urgently called on the Angolan Government and the
rebel UNITA to "cooperate immediately and fully" with U.N.
peacekeepers in search and rescue of 14 people aboard a
U.N.-chartered cargo plane that crashed near the war zone in
Angola.
</P>
<P>
In a statement read to the press here, the president of the
Security Council for the month of December, Jassim Buallay of
Bahrain, said, "Council members urgently call on the Government of
Angola and UNITA to cooperate immediately and fully with the
United Nations Observer Mission in Angola (MONUA) in the search
and rescue mission."
</P>
<P>
The statement voiced the Security Council's "deepest concern
about the fate of the crew and passengers" aboard the missing
plane, saying that "any further delay jeopardizes the lives of
possible survivors."
</P>
<P>
The statement expressed the concern that "there has been no
effective action undertaken in order to find out what happened to
three previous planes that disappeared over territory controlled
by UNITA," namely the National Union for Total Independence of
Angola.
</P>
<P>
"Council members renewed their appeal to the Government of
Angola and UNITA to guarantee the safety and freedom of movement
of MONUA personnel, and encourage the (U.N.) Secretary-General to
take additional steps to ensure adequate security and protection
for its personnel," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Also Tuesday, a MONUA statement, issued in the Angolan capital
of Luanda, said, "There could be survivors" aboard the plane,
which went missing Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The special representative of the U.N. Secretary-General in
Angola, Issa Diallo, "appeals in the strongest terms" to the
Angolan Government and UNITA to stop fighting around the crash
site, so that U.N. peacekeepers can visit the site of the accident
and try to save lives of the 14 persons, including four crew
members.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Spokesman's Office Tuesday disclosed a list of
nationalities of the missing passengers and crew members.
Passengers included three Angolans, an Australian, two Russians, a
Cameroonian, an Egyptian, a Namibian and a Zambian. The crew was
made up of an Angolan, a Bolivian, a Filipino and a South African.
</P>
<P>
The C-130 aircraft crashed 10 minutes after takeoff near the
central highland city Huambo, about 480 kilometers southeast of
Luanda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
